m.au/sport/afl/tasmania-set-to-apply-for-a-provisional-afl-licence-20190823-p52k4n.html|title=Tasmania set to apply for a provisional AFL licence|last=Wilson|first=Caroline|date=2019-08-23|website=The Age|language=en|access-date=2019-08-27}}</ref>\n| owners          = \n| president       = \n| chairman        = \n| ceo             = \n| coach           = [[Adrian Fletcher]] (TAC Cup)\n| captain         = \n| ground          = [[Bellerive Oval]], [[Hobart]]\n| capacity        = 19,500\n| ground2         = [[York Park]], [[Launceston, Tasmania|Launceston]]\n| capacity2       = 21,000\n| ground3         = Macquarie Point Stadium, Hobart (proposed)\n| capacity3       = 30,000\n| formerground    = \n| span            = \n| formerground2   = \n| span2           = \n| formerground3   = \n| span3           = \n| formerground4   = \n| span4           = \n| trainingground  = \n| trainingground2 = \n| trainingground3 = \n| premierships    = \n| kit_alt1        = \n| pattern_b1      = \n| pattern_sh1     = \n| pattern_so1     = \n| body1           = \n| shorts1         = \n| socks1          = \n| pattern_name1   = <!--optional, default: Home -->\n| kit_alt2        = \n| pattern_b2      = \n| pattern_sh2     = \n| pattern_so2     = \n| body2           = \n| shorts2         = \n| socks2          = \n| pattern_name2   = <!--optional, default: Away -->\n| kit_alt3        = \n| pattern_b3      = \n| pattern_sh3     = \n| pattern_so3     = \n| body3           = \n| shorts3         = \n| socks3          = \n| pattern_name3   = <!--optional, default: Alternate -->\n| url             = \n| jumper          = \n| current         = \n}}\n\nThe '''Tasmanian AFL bid''' refers to several [[Australian rules football]] teams that have proposed to eventually join the [[Australian Football League]] (AFL) and the [[AFL Women's]] (AFLW).<ref name=\"THE DEVILS ARE BACK - AFL Tasmania\">{{Cite news|url=http://www.afltas.com.au/the-devils-are-back/|title=THE DEVILS ARE BACK - AFL Tasmania|date=2018-09-21|work=AFL Tasmania|access-date=2018-09-21|language=en-US}}</ref> Proposals have been made on several occasions since the expansion of the Victorian Football League into an Australia-wide competition started in 1987.\n\n== Australian rules football in Tasmania ==\n[[File:Tasmania_at_Adelaide_Carnival,_1911.jpg|thumb|right|250px|[[Tasmania]] has been a stronghold of [[Australian rules football]] since the 1860s. Pictured is the 1911 Tasmanian state side from the [[1911 Adelaide Carnival|Adelaide carnival]] where they beat the Western Australian state team on [[Adelaide Oval]].]]\n{{main|Australian rules football in Tasmania}}\nAustralian rules football has been played in Tasmania as long as the mainland states with the first clubs formed in the early 1860s. The state hosted the national football carnival in 1924, 1947 and 1966.{{main|Tasmania v Victoria (1960)}}\nIn 1960, the Tasmanian state side defeated a Victorian state side made up from some of the best players from the Victorian Football League.\n\nThe largest attendance at a football game in Tasmania was set at the [[1979 TANFL season#Grand Final|1979 TANFL Grand Final]] with 24,968 spectators watching [[Clarence Football Club|Clarence]] defeat [[Glenorchy Football Club|Glenorchy]] by three points at [[North Hobart Oval]].\n\n==AFL team proposals==\n===1990: Tasmania defeats Victoria===\n{| style=\"margin-right:4px; margin-top:8px; float:left; border:1px #000 solid; border-radius:8px; background:#fff; font-family:Verdana; font-size:8pt; text-align:center;\"\n|-\n| width=200 | ''1990 Tasmania v. Victoria''|| ''G'' || ''B'' || ''Score''\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left\" |'''[[Tasmania Australian rules football team|Tasmania]]''' || '''20''' || '''14''' || '''134'''\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left\" | [[Victoria Australian rules football team|Victoria]] || 14 || 17 || 101\n|-\n| Venue: [[Bellerive Oval]]\n| colspan=3 | \n| colspan=3 |\n|}\t\nOn the 24 June 1990, Tasmania's state team defeated the Victorian state team in front of a full house at Bellerive Oval fuelling the first calls for the state to house its own AFL team.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article120894545 |title=SPORT Belconnen loses way to Bullants |newspaper=[[The Canberra Times]] |volume=64 |issue=20,152 |location=Australian Capital Territory, Australia |date=25 June 1990 |accessdate=23 February 2018 |page=23 |via=National Library of Australia}}</ref> [[Colin Alexander]] kicked 4 goals for Tasmania during the match.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://australianfootball.com/articles/view/30+years+on+-+1990+State+of+Orgin:+Tasmania+v+Victoria/49|title=Australian Football - 30 years on - 1990 State of Orgin: Tasmania v Victoria|website=australianfootball.com|language=en|access-date=2018-09-21}}</ref>\n\n===1991\u20131997: 14th, 15th & 16th AFL licences===\nIn 1991, Fitzroy played three games in Tasmania.\n\nIn 1992 Roger Curtis, then president of successful Tasmanian State League side Clarence, flagged the inevitable decline of Tasmanian football without the presence of its own AFL side.<ref name=\"nla.gov.au\">{{cite news|url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article118167066|title=Troubled Tassie wants its own team in AFL|date=29 January 1992|newspaper=[[The Canberra Times]]|accessdate=23 February 2018|issue=20,744|location=Australian Capital Territory, Australia|volume=66|page=38|via=National Library of Australia}}</ref> Curtis said that \"The only way to get the kids playing football here is to give them access to the best product available and that, of course, is AFL football...You would have to call the side 'Tasmania' as fans simply won't follow a relocated side with its traditional name, even if it was Collingwood\".<ref name=\"nla.gov.au\"/>\n\nIn April 1994 The Tasmanian Sports Minister, Peter Hodgman, spoke to the AFL about the possible introduction of a local team to the league and had raised the possibility of state funding.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article118112819 |title=AFL clubs oppose push for more sides |newspaper=[[The Canberra Times]] |volume=69 |issue=21,546 |location=Australian Capital Territory, Australia |date=13 April 1994 |accessdate=23 February 2018 |page=38 |via=National Library of Australia}}</ref>\n\nBetween 1994 and 1997 the bid was prepared for a Tasmanian team that involved the construction of a 30,000-capacity stadium at the [[Hobart Showground]]s in [[Glenorchy, Tasmania|Glenorchy]], at the cost of approximately $30 million.<ref name=\"newstadium\">{{cite web\n  | title = Ditch AFL bid: clubs\n  | publisher = Examiner \n  | date = 20 February 1998\n  | url = http://www.examiner.com.au/news/local/sport/general/ditch-afl-bid-clubs/1316425.aspx\n  | accessdate =20 April 2009}}</ref>\n\n===2008\u20132011: Tasmania beaten by Gold Coast and Western Sydney===\n{{Quote box\n | quote  = \"Tasmanians already watch AFL\"<br /><br />\n | source = '''[[Andrew Demetriou]]''', former AFL CEO and {{AFL Nor}} and {{AFL Haw}} player responding to questions regarding why Tasmania is not a priority in 2009.<ref>https://www.foxsports.com.au/afl/brisbane-lions-star-mitch-robinson-on-tasmanias-footy-crisis/news-story/752c43c07c7b1ee51ed3865209966c29</ref>\n | align  = right\n| width  = 35%\n }}\nThe AFL's continued rejection of the Tasmanian AFL team has raised significant controversy, with the [[Government of Australia]] launching a [[Senate of Australia|Senate]] inquiry in 2008 which [[AFL Commission]] CEO [[Andrew Demetriou]] and chairman [[Mike Fitzpatrick (footballer)|Mike Fitzpatrick]] both declined to attend.<ref name=\"themercury.com.au\">{{cite web|url=http://www.themercury.com.au/article/2009/03/28/63835_sport-news.html |title=Soccer could beat AFL |work=The Mercury |date=28 March 2009 |accessdate=24 October 2011}}</ref> At the enquiry, Tasmanian senator [[Kerry O'Brien (politician)|Kerry O'Brien]] brought into question the AFL's commitment to the game in Tasmania, and stated that he believed that with continued neglect, the popularity of [[Association football in Tasmania|soccer]] could overtake [[Australian rules football in Tasmania]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.themercury.com.au/article/2009/03/28/63835_sport-news.html|title=Soccer could beat AFL|date=28 March 2009}}</ref>  There are already more children playing soccer than Australian rules football in Tasmania.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.theage.com.au/news/soccer/soccer-on-rise-as-afl-treads-water/2006/12/31/1167500010371.html |title=Soccer on rise as AFL treads water |first= Tim |last=Colebatch|date=1 January 2007}}</ref>\n\nThe AFL argued that the New South Wales based participation numbers were in excess of that in Tasmania,<ref>[http://www.aph.gov.au/Senate/committee/rrat_ctte/afl_tasmania/report/e03.htm#anc2 Answers to questions: AFL \u2013 Mr Phil Martin (question 4)]</ref> furthering their argument that a team in Western Sydney was a higher priority. The Senate enquiry found that insurmountable cultural barriers would make such a move non-viable.<ref>[http://www.thewest.com.au/default.aspx?MenuID=4&ContentID=151020 AFL tells Senate to mind their own business]</ref>\n\nIn April 2008, Tasmania's former premier [[Paul Lennon]] revived the push for an AFL team by travelling to AFL House in [[Melbourne]] where the latest bid was officially launched. Although Lennon subsequently retired in May, the responsibility of steering the bid went to Economic Development Minister [[Paula Wriedt]]. Wriedt said Tasmania only made the case for a Tasmanian team, and were not trying to beat the Gold Coast or Greater Western Sydney to be the 17th or 18th club.<ref>{{cite web\n| url = http://www.theaustralian.news.com.au/story/0,25197,24029484-2722,00.html\n| title = Tasmania's bid for AFL team faltering\n| accessdate =14 August 2008\n| author = \n| date = 16 July 2008\n| publisher = The Australian\n}}</ref>\n\nAFL CEO Andrew Demetriou has said: \"They probably do deserve a team, we shouldn't dismiss the contribution that Tasmania has made to our game... They are absolutely entitled to put forward a proposal, but the commission has already decided where the 17th and 18th teams are going.\"<ref>{{cite web\n| url = http://www.canberratimes.com.au/news/local/news/general/afl-expansion-plans-yet-to-include-tassie/812001.aspx\n| title = AFL expansion plans yet to include Tassie\n| accessdate =14 August 2008\n| author = \n| date = 16 July 2008\n| publisher = The Canberra Times\n}}</ref>\n\nThe bid received a significant boost on 30 July 2008, with the announcement that the confectionery company [[Mars, Incorporated|Mars]] committed to being the proposed club's major sponsor.<ref>{{cite web\n| url = http://www.abc.net.au/news/stories/2008/08/01/2320914.htm\n| title = Tasmania given sweet boost to AFL bid\n| accessdate =14 August 2008\n| author = \n| date = 1 August 2008\n| publisher = ABC News\n}}</ref>\n\nSome media commentators have speculated that the AFL holds Tasmania open as a soft target for relocation of struggling Melbourne clubs. In 2010, there was increased speculation due to [[North Melbourne Football Club|North Melbourne]]'s commitment to move four home games annually to Hobart's [[Bellerive Oval]].<ref>[http://www.theroar.com.au/2010/07/29/dont-knock-north-for-looking-at-hobart/ Don't knock North for looking at Hobart], The Roar, Retrieved on 29 July 2010.</ref>\n\n=== 2011\u20132017: Off the AFL agenda and bare draft crop ===\nIn April 2014, AFL deputy chief executive [[Gillon McLachlan]] said he supported a \"single team representing Tasmania\". He stated Tasmania would be the next team to join the AFL, but that this would not happen for at least a decade.<ref>[http://www.examiner.com.au/story/2220931/no-tasmanian-afl-team-for-at-least-a-decade-says-mclachlan/ The Examiner \u2013 No Tasmanian AFL team for at least a decade, says McLachlan]</ref>\n\nIn 2016, the Garlick report confirmed that a stand-alone Tasmanian team would have to wait until current broadcast deals expire at the end of the 2022 season to enter the AFL.\n\nFor the [[2016 AFL draft|2016 AFL National Draft]] no Tasmanian players were drafted. The following year only one player was drafted.\n\nIn April 2017, the Tasmanian Government indicated its interest in relocating the [[Gold Coast Suns]] to Tasmania in the event the club collapses.<ref>[http://www.heraldsun.com.au/sport/afl/teams/gold-coast/tasmania-ready-to-swoop-for-the-gold-coast-suns-in-renewed-push-for-standalone-afl-team/news-story/85accae5a95877175cefd47ce9be6580 Tasmania launches new bid for AFL team, offering to relocate Gold Coast Suns]</ref>\n\nIn September 2017, the AFL awarded a licence for an [[AFL Women's]] team for the 2019 AFLW  season for a combined \"Tasmania-North Melbourne\" team. The submission for a licence was a joint project of the [[North Melbourne Football Club]] and the [[Government of Tasmania]].<ref name=\"ABC News - 27 September 2017 - AFLW: Tasmania-North Melbourne and Geelong win licences to field teams from 2019\">{{cite news|url=http://www.abc.net.au/news/2017-09-27/tasmania-nth-melb-geelong-win-new-aflw-licences-for-2019/8992508|title=AFLW: Tasmania-North Melbourne and Geelong win licences to field teams from 2019|date=27 September 2017|work=[[ABC News (Australia)]]|publisher=[[Australian Broadcasting Corporation]]|accessdate=27 September 2017}}</ref>\n\n=== Early 2018: AFL steering committee and A-League team bid ===\n\nIn early 2018, [[AFL Tasmania]] CEO Rob Auld resigned, and the following day Burnie and Devonport withdrew from the Tasmanian State League, citing lack of funding \nmaking them unable to field sides, thus leaving the competition without any team from North Western Tasmania.\n\nThe same week, AFL CEO [[Gillon McLachlan]] was quoted as saying he \u201chad a really clear plan for Tasmania\u201d; that week, the [[AFLX]] launch took place as well as an announcement that the Gold Coast Suns received $25 million in subsidies for 2017.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.afr.com/business/sport/the-afl-propped-up-gold-coast-suns-with-25m-after-sponsorship-woes-20180201-h0s15t|title=The AFL propped up on Gold Coast Suns with $25m after sponsorship woes|date=2018-02-04|work=Financial Review|access-date=2018-02-23|language=en-US}}</ref>\n\nOn 16 February 2018 the [[A-League]], a key rival of the AFL, announced it would expand its competition by two teams for the upcoming 2019-20 season and flagging that a Tasmanian bid was a key contender, though the bid was rejected in June 2018 after being cut from the [[Football Federation Australia|FFA]] shortlist.\n\nOn the 23 February 2018 during an interview on SEN, newly appointed AFL Tasmania CEO Trisha Squires did not have a position on whether Tasmania was better off with two fly-in-fly-out Victorian sides or its own side.<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.sen.com.au/news/2018/02/23/afl-tassie-boss-has-no-idea-whats-best-for-footy/|title=AFL Tassie boss has no idea what's best for footy|access-date=2018-02-23|language=en}}</ref> She also described talk of a standalone Tasmanian team as a \"distraction\".<ref name=\":2\" />\n\nSubsequent to these events, a steering committee was formed in March. On 3 July 2018, the committee delivered its findings.\n<ref>[https://www.examiner.com.au/story/5503002/tasmanian-fans-must-help-football-revival/?cs=96 Steering committee aims to unite Tasmanian football]</ref>\n\nMcLachlan announced the following recommendations to rebuild and unify Tasmanian football over the next three years:<ref name=Siri1>[http://amp.abc.net.au/article/9931164 AFL boss Gillon McLachlan to deliver Tasmanian football blueprint]</ref>\n\n*The AFL will invest an extra $1.4 million in Tasmania in 2019.\n*Create three regional administration hubs to help run community football.\n*Generate AFL affiliation with community leagues.\n*The TSL will remain the state's top-tier competition and continue to receive AFL funding.\n*Extend Tasmania's junior pathways from under-12s to under-18s with more opportunities to play in intrastate tournaments. Junior levies will also be removed.\n*A full-time under-18s Mariners program with Tasmania to compete in the TAC Cup from 2019.\n*Tasmania was granted a provisional licence to re-enter the VFL in 2021.\n*There will be greater investment in the talent pathway for women, with a girls\u2019 side to take part in TAC Cup from 2020.\n*A Tasmanian advisory board, made up of Tasmanians, will be set up to oversee the changes\n*All programs are to be re-branded under a name to be decided by the Tasmanian people.\n\nMclachlan also stated the success of these plans would help determine a potential date for a Tasmanian team to enter the AFL.<ref name=Siri1/>\n\n=== Late 2018: Political and social pressure and branding announcement  ===\nSeveral days later, [[Leader of the Opposition (Australia)|Opposition Leader]] [[Bill Shorten]] pledged $25 million in funding for a Tasmanian AFL team, contingent on the [[Australian Labor Party|Labor Party]] winning the [[2019 Australian federal election|2019 federal election]].<ref>[http://mobile.abc.net.au/news/2018-07-07/shortens-$25m-tasmanian-afl-pledge/9953384?pfmredir=sm Shorten's $25m Tasmanian AFL pledge welcomed, but doubts powerbrokers will be swayed]</ref>\n\nOn the 26 June 2018, Tasmanian Nationals Senator [[Steve Martin (Australian politician)|Steve Martin]] moved a motion calling for the AFL to commission business plans for the inclusion of a Tasmanian team in the men's and women's national league.<ref name=\":3\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.themercury.com.au/subscribe/news/1/?sourceCode=TMWEB_WRE170_a&dest=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.themercury.com.au%2Fnews%2Fpolitics%2Fnew-national-senator-steve-martin-makes-play-for-tassie-afl-team%2Fnews-story%2Fb2b253aa56459ed83dfe8c97cc8bde34&memtype=anonymous&mode=premium&nk=f8f5161f4e5b8ef324f383f77558e1a9-1555552592|title=Subscribe to The Mercury|website=www.themercury.com.au|access-date=2019-04-18}}</ref> At the time Senator Martin did so with the support of Coalition and Labor senators.<ref name=\":3\" />\n\nOn the 21 September 2018, Trisha Squires announced that representative Tasmanian football teams administered by [[AFL Tasmania]] would be known as the Tasmania Devils and would wear green, yellow and maroon.<ref name=\"THE DEVILS ARE BACK - AFL Tasmania\">{{Cite news|url=http://www.afltas.com.au/the-devils-are-back/|title=THE DEVILS ARE BACK - AFL Tasmania|date=2018-09-21|work=AFL Tasmania|access-date=2018-09-21|language=en-US}}</ref>\n\nOn 11 October 2018, [[Adrian Fletcher]] was named as the Tasmania Devils [[TAC Cup]] coach.\n\n===Early 2019: Guidelines set by AFL===\nOn 22 March 2019, Caroline Wilson broke the story that the AFL had set [[Will Hodgman]], Tasmanian Premier, guideline requirements to house an AFL team being:<ref name=\":4\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.theage.com.au/sport/afl/no-longer-if-but-when-push-grows-for-a-tasmanian-afl-team-20190322-p516mb.html|title='No longer if but when': Push grows for a Tasmanian AFL team|last=Wilson|first=Caroline|date=2019-03-22|website=The Age|language=en|access-date=2019-04-18}}</ref>\n\n* At least 50,000 members.\n* Up front capital of $40,000,000.\n* A unified Tasmanian football community.\n* AFL standard venues.\n* A minimum of 10 Tasmanian players in the AFL.\n* Designing a respectful exit strategy for current [[Fly-in fly-out|FIFO]] Victorian tenants [[North Melbourne Football Club|North Melbourne]] and [[Hawthorn Football Club|Hawthorn]].\n\nIt was noted that Tasmania had 90,000 members for the existing mainland AFL clubs in 2018.\n\n=== Late 2019: Taskforce formed ===\nIn mid-2019, a taskforce made up of people from the Australian business community was formed with the intent of gaining an AFL licence.<ref name=\":5\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.theage.com.au/sport/afl/riewoldt-to-join-tasmanian-afl-taskforce-20190625-p52171.html|title=Riewoldt to join Tasmanian AFL taskforce|last=Ryan|first=Peter|date=2019-06-25|website=The Age|language=en|access-date=2019-08-20}}</ref> The taskforce is being chaired by [[Brett Godfrey]].<ref name=\":5\" />\n\nThese taskforce members were:<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.examiner.com.au/story/6205390/task-force-meet-for-first-time/|title=Task-force meet for first time|last=Partridge|first=Josh|date=2019-06-07|website=The Examiner|language=en|access-date=2019-08-20}}</ref>\n\n* [[Brett Godfrey]] (chair)\n* Errol Stewart\n* Grant O'Brien\n* Julie Kay\n* Paul Eriksson\n* James Henderson\n\nThe [[Tourism Industry Council of Tasmania]] also backed the push for a stand alone Tasmanian AFL team, saying it would have substantial positive impacts on multiple facets of the state's economy, and reiterated that \"A Tasmanian AFL team [should] play out of both the North and South of the state, with a relatively even number of games in both Hobart and Launceston each year...We believe this principle must be accepted as fundamental to further discussion about an AFL team in Tasmania to completely destruct any perceptions of a 'Southern' or 'Northern' team...Rather than seeing this as a challenge in the formation of the team, we see it as one of its strengths in being a unifying force within the state and maximising the resources of all regions.\" <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.examiner.com.au/story/6296117/states-peak-tourism-body-enters-tasmanian-afl-team-debate/|title=State's peak tourism body enters Tasmanian AFL team debate|last=Inglis|first=Rob|date=2019-07-27|website=The Examiner|language=en|access-date=2019-08-20}}</ref>'\n\nOn 16 May 2019, the AFL applied for a [[trade mark]] with [[IP Australia]] for the Tasmania Devils logo, sparking speculation that this would be the logo for a new Tasmanian AFL team. <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://bennettandco.com.au/areas/intellectual/the-afls-new-tasmania-devils-logo-why-sporting-clubs-should-care-about-trade-marks/|title=The AFL's New Tasmania Devils Logo - Why sporting clubs should care about trade marks|last=Stewart|first=David|date=2020-09-04|website= Bennett + Co|language=en|access-date=2020-04-14}}</ref> \n\nOn 23 August 2019, Caroline Wilson reported that the taskforce would be applying for a provisional AFL licence before the end of the year.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.theage.com.au/sport/afl/tasmania-set-to-apply-for-a-provisional-afl-licence-20190823-p52k4n.html|title=Tasmania set to apply for a provisional AFL licence|last=Wilson|first=Caroline|date=2019-08-23|website=The Age|language=en|access-date=2019-08-27}}</ref> The taskforce has aimed to enter the competition in 2025, when the extended broadcast rights deal expires. Plans to build a new stadium and training facility at Hobart's Macquarie Point were also revealed, while the VFL team's entry could also be delayed to 2022 to develop local talent. On the 8 November 2019 the Taskforce run petition surpassed 60,000 pledges in support of a Tasmanian AFL team.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.themercury.com.au/news/tasmania-to-cut-apron-strings-by-joining-the-afl-as-its-first-sporting-goal/news-story/5f5be82ad9931347b38eff23fe68ef20|title=Tasmania to cut apron strings by joining the AFL as its first sporting goal|last=Stubbs|first=Brett|date=8 November 2019|website=themercury.com.au|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\n=== 2020: Coronavirus impact ===\n\nDue to the [[2019-20 coronavirus pandemic]], Collingwood President Eddie McGuire has stated it could take ten years for the AFL and its clubs to recover, likely pushing back Tasmania's AFL team aspirations in the short to medium term. <ref> [https://www.theadvocate.com.au/story/6688736/tassie-afl-team-hopes-fading-says-eddie-mcguire/ Tasmania to wait for AFL hopes] </ref> In this regard, Nick Riewoldt stated Tasmania still has an opportunity to contribute to the game and its recovery.\n\nWhile Tasmanian AFL Taskforce chairman Brett Godfrey has promised to continue pushing Tasmania's case at the appropriate time, he remains optimistic about a 2025 entry date, and has also expressed interest in a Tasmanian team entering the competition earlier in the event an existing AFL club collapses as a result of the crisis.\n\nSince the crisis has effectively forced Tasmania to close its borders, the prospect of Hawthorn and North Melbourne moving their Tasmanian games to Melbourne has been raised; a decision on this is yet to be finalised, and the 2020 season was suspended on March 22.\n\n== Honour board ==\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|+\n! colspan=\"8\" |Tasmania Devils Honour Board\n|-\n! colspan=\"8\" |[[NAB League]]\n|-\n!Year\n!Position\n!W-L-D\n!%\n!Coach\n!Captain\n!Best & Fairest\n!Leading Goal Kicker\n|-\n|[[2019 NAB League season|2019]]\n|14/18 (12/13)\n|4-11-0, lost Wildcard Final\n|80\n|[[Adrian Fletcher]]<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.examiner.com.au/story/5698802/fletcher-to-drive-devils-full-time-tac-cup-return/|title=Fletcher to drive Devils' full-time TAC Cup return|last=Martin|first=Corey|date=2018-10-12|work=The Examiner|access-date=2018-10-24|language=en}}</ref>\n|Nic Baker<br />Jared Dakin<br />Oliver Davis\n|\n|Jackson Callow (24)<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://websites.sportstg.com/comp_info.cgi?c=1-3020-0-518307-0&a=STATS|title=Season Statistics for 2019 NAB League|website=SportsTG|language=en|access-date=2019-06-07}}</ref>\n|-\n|2020\n|\n|\n|\n|Cameron Joyce\n|\n|\n|\n|}\n\n== VFL teams ==\n\n=== Tasmanian Devils Football Club (2001 \u2013 2008) ===\n{{main|Tasmanian Devils Football Club}}\nIn 2001 the [[Tasmanian Devils Football Club]] was formed and competed in the [[Victorian Football League]] until 2008.\n\nDuring the 1990s, Tasmania had shown strong interest in joining the AFL and after rejected bids in 1995 and 1997 the [[Australian Football League]] instigated the formation a Tasmanian team for the newly re-constructed [[Victorian Football League]]. The Tasmanian Devils Football Club formed in 2001 and was admitted into the VFL in its inaugural season the same year. The AFL continues to own the club.\n\nThe nickname \"Devils\" was chosen as the moniker for the club after the tenacious marsupial predator the [[Tasmanian devil]] which is indigenous to the island of Tasmania. The club colours green, red, gold (and black) were inspired by the original [[Interstate matches in Australian rules football|State of Origin]] \"map\" guernsey and are also Tasmania's sporting colours.\n\nThe Devils established home grounds in both [[Hobart]] and [[Launceston, Tasmania|Launceston]] to deal with the long-standing north-south rivalry. Originally northern home games were played at Ulverstone, Devonport, Burnie and at Launceston's [[Aurora Stadium]] while [[North Hobart Oval]] hosted games in the south. At the end of the 2005 season the team moved from North Hobart Oval to [[Bellerive Oval]] for home games in the south and began playing all northern home games at Aurora Stadium.\n\n2001 and 2002 brought mediocre results but, under the direction of coach [[Matthew Armstrong (Australian footballer)|Matthew Armstrong]], the Devils made the finals for the first time in 2003, finishing a respectable third. The 2004 and 2005 seasons saw the Devils again making the finals.\n\nAt the start of the 2006 season the Devils and the [[Australian Football League]]'s [[North Melbourne Football Club]] began a [[Australian Football League reserves affiliations|partial alignment]], allowing North Melbourne listed players to play for Tasmania when not selected in the seniors, and arrangement which lasted from 2006 until 2007. This was unpopular among local fans, significantly harming the popularity of the club; and the season proved to be a disappointment on-field, with the Devils finishing ninth and missing the finals.<ref name=\"wade1\">{{cite news|newspaper=The Mercury|location=Hobart, TAS|title=The power and the passion: Scott Wade reflects on a career at the coalface of Tasmanian football|date=12 March 2016|accessdate=31 July 2016|url=http://www.themercury.com.au/sport/afl/the-power-and-the-passion-scott-wade-reflects-on-a-career-at-the-coalface-of-tasmanian-football/news-story/76cf3fb235222e7335338bc1a8b6dbb4}}</ref><ref name=\"wade2\">{{cite web|title=AFL Tasmania chief Scott Wade's resignation was a 'mutual decision', AFL says|url=http://www.abc.net.au/news/2016-03-09/afl-tasmania-chief-scott-wade-quits/7229750|date=9 March 2016|author=Scott Rollinson|publisher=Australian Broadcasting Corporation}}</ref> During the 2006 season, Armstrong stepped down as coach due to internal pressure from the playing group, ending his six-year term as Devils coach. [[North Hobart Football Club|North Hobart]] premiership coach and former Devil [[Brendon Bolton]] was made stand in coach for the remainder of the year.<ref name=\"Tasmania Devils history\">[http://australianfootball.com/clubs/info/Tasmania/249 Tasmania Devils history]</ref>\n\nTasmanian and former [[Sydney Swans|Sydney Swan]] [[Daryn Cresswell]] was named coach of the club for 2007 after a successful career as an assistant coach at [[Geelong Football Club|Geelong]] and the [[Brisbane Lions]]; however, hampered in part by Cresswell's off-field issues which included a gambling addiction and eventual fraud conviction, the club finished wooden spooners both seasons he coached the team, winning only six of a total 34 games.<ref name=\"wade1\" /><ref name=\"wade2\" />\n\nAt the end of the 2008 season, AFL Tasmania decided to withdraw the Devils from the VFL competition in favour of restarting a new Tasmanian league encompassing the entire state.<ref name=\"Tasmania Devils history\"/>\n\n=== Tasmania Devils (2021 or 2022) ===\nThe AFL plans on fielding a Tasmanian team in the Victorian Football League in 2021 or 2022 as a potential precursor to a team entering the Australian Football League.\n\n== Victorian AFL clubs in Tasmania ==\nAs Tasmania is the last Australian state to house an AFL team, and is also a heartland state of the code (unlike New South Wales and Queensland), the league has often used the state for Melbourne-based clubs to host games in Tasmania subsidised by local and the Tasmanian state governments. Both of the current deals with Hawthorn and North Melbourne will expire in 2021.<ref>[https://www.abc.net.au/news/2019-03-20/tasmanian-afl-dream-alive-after-gil-mclachlan-quip/10915680 Are all signs pointing to a Tasmanian AFL team?]</ref>\n\n*[[Fitzroy Football Club|Fitzroy]] (1991\u20131992)\n*[[Hawthorn Football Club|Hawthorn]] (2001\u2013present)\n*[[St Kilda Football Club|St Kilda]] (2003\u20132006)\n*[[North Melbourne Football Club|North Melbourne]] (2012\u2013present)\n\n== Supporters ==\n{| class=\"wikitable\" align=\"right\" style=\"font-size: 80%\"\n! colspan=\"3\" |Guernsey sponsors\n|-\n!Period\n!Front sponsor\n!Back sponsor\n|-\n!2019\n| AFL Tasmania + NAB || Cripps Nubake\n|}\nTasmanian news website and newspaper ''[[The Mercury (Hobart)|The Mercury]]'' has been a vocal supporter of the bid.<ref>{{cite news\n| url = http://www.news.com.au/mercury/story/0,22884,23355142-5016971,00.html\n| title = Our crusade to end Tassie's footy snub\n| accessdate =14 August 2008\n| date = 11 March 2008\n| publisher = The Mercury\n|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080511164906/http://www.news.com.au/mercury/story/0,22884,23355142-5016971,00.html\n|archivedate=11 May 2008\n| quote = ''And today ... the Mercury launches its season-long campaign, Tasmania \u2013 It's Time, to reignite the push for a Tasmanian team in the AFL.''\n}}</ref><ref>[http://www.themercury.com.au/sport/afl/cmon-tassie-we-need-a-team-effort/story-fnj4f7h7-1226862240976 The Mercury \u2013 C\u2019mon Tassie, we need a team effort]</ref>\n[[Kevin Sheedy (Australian footballer)|Kevin Sheedy]] has argued that Tasmania is not too small for an AFL team. He stated that population is irrelevant, and that a Tasmanian side could draw support from abroad in a similar way to the [[Green Bay Packers]].<ref name=\":0\">[http://www.abc.net.au/news/stories/2007/06/14/1951493.htm Tasmania not too small for an AFL team: Sheedy]</ref> In 2008 Tasmanian bank [[MyState Financial]] offered $300,000 over three years in sponsorship of a team.<ref name=\":1\">{{cite news|title=Tas bid gains momentum|url=http://www.theadvocate.com.au/story/672352/tas-bid-gains-momentum/|accessdate=18 January 2015|publisher=The Advocate|date=26 August 2008}}</ref>\n\n=== Government supporters ===\n* Tasmanian Government \u2013 $19,000,000 over 5 years (2015 deal with [[Hawthorn Football Club|Hawthorn]])<ref>{{Cite web|title = Tasmanian Government signs new five-year deal with Hawthorn|url = http://www.themercury.com.au/sport/afl/tasmanian-government-signs-new-five-year-deal-with-hawthorn/story-fnj4f7h7-1227465237561|accessdate = 2015-09-28}}</ref>\n* Tasmanian Government \u2013 $2,500,000 over 5 years (2017 deal with {{AFL Nor}} Women's team)<ref>http://www.abc.net.au/news/2017-09-27/tassie-kangaroos-tasmanias-new-afl-team/8994214</ref>\n* Hobart City Council \u2013 $600,000 over 2 years (2014 deal with [[North Melbourne Football Club|North Melbourne]])<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.abc.net.au/news/2014-08-26/north-melbourne-deal-seals-three-games-a-year-in-hobart/5696024|title=North Melbourne deal seals three AFL games a year in Hobart|website=ABC News|accessdate=2015-09-28}}</ref>\n* Spirit of Tasmania \u2013 $1,800,000 over 3 years (2016 deal with North Melbourne)<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.northweststar.com.au/story/3737927/north-melbourne-set-to-beat-hawthorn-to-tasmanian-academy/?cs=12|title=North Melbourne set to beat Hawthorn to Tasmanian academy|last=Wilson|first=Caroline|date=2016-02-18|work=The North West Star|access-date=2018-02-23|language=en}}</ref>\n\n=== Corporate support ===\n* [[Mars, Incorporated|MARS]] \u2013 $4,000,000 over three years (2008 proposal)<ref>{{Cite news|url = http://www.heraldsun.com.au/sport/afl/tassie-planets-align/story-e6frf9jf-1111117073738|title = Tasmanian AFL team secures major sponsor|date =31 July 2008 |accessdate = 4 October 2015|work= Herald Sun |publisher = |last = Pierik|first = Jon }}</ref>\n* MyState Financial \u2013 $300,000 (2008 proposal)<ref name=\":1\" />\n\n=== Media supporters ===\n* Kevin Sheedy<ref name=\":0\"/>\n* Tim Lane<ref>{{Cite web|url = http://www.themercury.com.au/news/tasmania/tasmania-should-cash-in-on-support-for-afl-team-says-leading-football-commentator-tim-lane/story-fnj4f7k1-1227432894273|title = Tasmania should cash in on support for AFL team, says leading football commentator Tim Lane|date = 8 July 2015|accessdate = |website = |publisher = |last = THOMAS-WILSON|first = SIMEON}}</ref>\n* Mitch Robinson\n* Nick Riewoldt\n* Matthew Richardson\n* Andy Maher\n* Caroline Wilson\n* Brian Carlton\n* Jack Riewoldt\n\n== Venues and travel==\n{{multiple image\n| align    = right\n| image1   = Bellerive oval hobart.jpg\n| width1   = 220\n| alt1     = \n| image2   = Hawthorn v Western Bulldogs - &nbsp;31st&nbsp;May&nbsp;2008 181.jpg\n| width2   = 195\n| alt2     = \n| footer   = Left: Bellerive Oval would serve as the club's home ground in Hobart.<br/>Right: Tasmania's potential second ground, UTAS Stadium (York Park) in Launceston.\n}}\nDue to the population split of Tasmania between Hobart and Launceston it has been proposed that a future Tasmania club use two home grounds Launceston and Hobart which are approximately 200&nbsp;km apart.\n\nIt has often been suggested that the home games could be split between the two population centres with Hobart hosting six games a year and Launceston hosting five.\n\n=== Hobart ===\nHobart is Tasmania's largest city with a population around 230,000 which is comparable to [[City of Greater Geelong|Greater Geelong]]. The record crowd for an Australian rules game in Hobart was 24,968 for the 1979 TANFL Grand Final at [[North Hobart Oval]]. In August 2019 a Tasmanian Parliamentary Committee heard from the Tasmanian Football Board regarding a new purpose built stadium at Macquarie Point as part of a bid for an AFL team.<ref>https://www.themercury.com.au/sport/local-sport/macquarie-point-multipurpose-stadium-would-be-ideal-for-tasmanian-afl-team-parliamentary-committee-hears/news-story/664be9ce62cd66c10efb611bab22a642</ref>\n\n=== Launceston ===\nLaunceston is the second largest city in Tasmania housing nearly 90,000 people which is comparable in population to the [[Division of Fremantle|Federal Division of Fremantle]]. The northern half of Tasmania is home to half the states population. It is the economic centre of Northern Tasmania. The record crowd for an Australian rules game in Launceston was 20,971 at York Park an AFL minor round fixture in 2006.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|2}}\n\n==External links==\n* [https://archive.today/20121231001808/http://www.tassiefootyteam.com.au/ Tasmanian Government official bid website]\n\n{{AFL}}\n{{Aussie Rules in Tasmania}}\n{{TAC Cup}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Tasmanian Afl Bid}}\n[[Category:Proposed VFL/AFL clubs]]\n[[Category:Australian rules football in Tasmania]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2011}}\n{{Use Australian English|date=August 2011}}\n\n{{Infobox Australian football club\n| clubname        = Tasmania Devils\n| image           = [[File:Tasmania_Devils_AFL_team_logo,_2018.jpg|200px]]<br />[[AFL Tasmania|AFL Tasmania's]] logo for [[Tasmania]]n teams.<ref name=\"THE DEVILS ARE BACK - AFL Tasmania\">{{Cite news|url=http://www.afltas.com.au/the-devils-are-back/|title=THE DEVILS ARE BACK - AFL Tasmania|date=2018-09-21|work=AFL Tasmania|access-date=2018-09-21|language=en-US}}</ref>\n| image_name      = \n| image_size      = \n| fullname        = Tasmania Football Club\n| formernames     = \n| nicknames       = Devils\n| formernicknames = \n| motto           = \n| clubsong        = \n| season          = \n| afterfinals     = \n| home&away       = \n| pre-season      = \n| topgoalkicker   = \n| bestandfairest  = \n| founded         =\n| dissolved       = \n| colours         = {{color box|#006a4e}} Bottle green<br />{{color box|#DDDD87}} Primrose<br />{{color box|maroon}} Maroon\n| league          = [[TAC Cup]] (2019)<ref name=\"THE DEVILS ARE BACK - AFL Tasmania\">{{Cite news|url=http://www.afltas.com.au/the-devils-are-back/|title=THE DEVILS ARE BACK - AFL Tasmania|date=2018-09-21|work=AFL Tasmania|access-date=2018-09-21|language=en-US}}</ref><br />[[TAC Cup]] women (2020)<ref name=\"THE DEVILS ARE BACK - AFL Tasmania\">{{Cite news|url=http://www.afltas.com.au/the-devils-are-back/|title=THE DEVILS ARE BACK - AFL Tasmania|date=2018-09-21|work=AFL Tasmania|access-date=2018-09-21|language=en-US}}</ref><br />[[Victorian Football League|VFL]] (2021 or 2022)<ref name=\"THE DEVILS ARE BACK - AFL Tasmania\">{{Cite news|url=http://www.afltas.com.au/the-devils-are-back/|title=THE DEVILS ARE BACK - AFL Tasmania|date=2018-09-21|work=AFL Tasmania|access-date=2018-09-21|language=en-US}}</ref><br />[[Australian Football League|AFL]] (TBA, target 2025) <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.theage.com.au/sport/afl/tasmania-set-to-apply-for-a-provisional-afl-licence-20190823-p52k4n.html|title=Tasmania set to apply for a provisional AFL licence|last=Wilson|first=Caroline|date=2019-08-23|website=The Age|language=en|access-date=2019-08-27}}</ref>\n| owners          = \n| president       = \n| chairman        = \n| ceo             = \n| coach           = [[Adrian Fletcher]] (TAC Cup)\n| captain         = \n| ground          = [[Bellerive Oval]], [[Hobart]]\n| capacity        = 19,500\n| ground2         = [[York Park]], [[Launceston, Tasmania|Launceston]]\n| capacity2       = 21,000\n| ground3         = Macquarie Point Stadium, Hobart (proposed)\n| capacity3       = 30,000\n| formerground    = \n| span            = \n| formerground2   = \n| span2           = \n| formerground3   = \n| span3           = \n| formerground4   = \n| span4           = \n| trainingground  = \n| trainingground2 = \n| trainingground3 = \n| premierships    = \n| kit_alt1        = \n| pattern_b1      = \n| pattern_sh1     = \n| pattern_so1     = \n| body1           = \n| shorts1         = \n| socks1          = \n| pattern_name1   = <!--optional, default: Home -->\n| kit_alt2        = \n| pattern_b2      = \n| pattern_sh2     = \n| pattern_so2     = \n| body2           = \n| shorts2         = \n| socks2          = \n| pattern_name2   = <!--optional, default: Away -->\n| kit_alt3        = \n| pattern_b3      = \n| pattern_sh3     = \n| pattern_so3     = \n| body3           = \n| shorts3         = \n| socks3          = \n| pattern_name3   = <!--optional, default: Alternate -->\n| url             = \n| jumper          = \n| current         = \n}}\n\nThe '''Tasmanian AFL bid''' refers to several [[Australian rules football]] teams that have proposed to eventually join the [[Australian Football League]] (AFL) and the [[AFL Women's]] (AFLW).<ref name=\"THE DEVILS ARE BACK - AFL Tasmania\">{{Cite news|url=http://www.afltas.com.au/the-devils-are-back/|title=THE DEVILS ARE BACK - AFL Tasmania|date=2018-09-21|work=AFL Tasmania|access-date=2018-09-21|language=en-US}}</ref> Proposals have been made on several occasions since the expansion of the Victorian Football League into an Australia-wide competition started in 1987.\n\n== Australian rules football in Tasmania ==\n[[File:Tasmania_at_Adelaide_Carnival,_1911.jpg|thumb|right|250px|[[Tasmania]] has been a stronghold of [[Australian rules football]] since the 1860s. Pictured is the 1911 Tasmanian state side from the [[1911 Adelaide Carnival|Adelaide carnival]] where they beat the Western Australian state team on [[Adelaide Oval]].]]\n{{main|Australian rules football in Tasmania}}\nAustralian rules football has been played in Tasmania as long as the mainland states with the first clubs formed in the early 1860s. The state hosted the national football carnival in 1924, 1947 and 1966.{{main|Tasmania v Victoria (1960)}}\nIn 1960, the Tasmanian state side defeated a Victorian state side made up from some of the best players from the Victorian Football League.\n\nThe largest attendance at a football game in Tasmania was set at the [[1979 TANFL season#Grand Final|1979 TANFL Grand Final]] with 24,968 spectators watching [[Clarence Football Club|Clarence]] defeat [[Glenorchy Football Club|Glenorchy]] by three points at [[North Hobart Oval]].\n\n==AFL team proposals==\n===1990: Tasmania defeats Victoria===\n{| style=\"margin-right:4px; margin-top:8px; float:left; border:1px #000 solid; border-radius:8px; background:#fff; font-family:Verdana; font-size:8pt; text-align:center;\"\n|-\n| width=200 | ''1990 Tasmania v. Victoria''|| ''G'' || ''B'' || ''Score''\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left\" |'''[[Tasmania Australian rules football team|Tasmania]]''' || '''20''' || '''14''' || '''134'''\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left\" | [[Victoria Australian rules football team|Victoria]] || 14 || 17 || 101\n|-\n| Venue: [[Bellerive Oval]]\n| colspan=3 | \n| colspan=3 |\n|}\t\nOn the 24 June 1990, Tasmania's state team defeated the Victorian state team in front of a full house at Bellerive Oval fuelling the first calls for the state to house its own AFL team.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article120894545 |title=SPORT Belconnen loses way to Bullants |newspaper=[[The Canberra Times]] |volume=64 |issue=20,152 |location=Australian Capital Territory, Australia |date=25 June 1990 |accessdate=23 February 2018 |page=23 |via=National Library of Australia}}</ref> [[Colin Alexander]] kicked 4 goals for Tasmania during the match.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://australianfootball.com/articles/view/30+years+on+-+1990+State+of+Orgin:+Tasmania+v+Victoria/49|title=Australian Football - 30 years on - 1990 State of Orgin: Tasmania v Victoria|website=australianfootball.com|language=en|access-date=2018-09-21}}</ref>\n\n===1991\u20131997: 14th, 15th & 16th AFL licences===\nIn 1991, Fitzroy played three games in Tasmania.\n\nIn 1992 Roger Curtis, then president of successful Tasmanian State League side Clarence, flagged the inevitable decline of Tasmanian football without the presence of its own AFL side.<ref name=\"nla.gov.au\">{{cite news|url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article118167066|title=Troubled Tassie wants its own team in AFL|date=29 January 1992|newspaper=[[The Canberra Times]]|accessdate=23 February 2018|issue=20,744|location=Australian Capital Territory, Australia|volume=66|page=38|via=National Library of Australia}}</ref> Curtis said that \"The only way to get the kids playing football here is to give them access to the best product available and that, of course, is AFL football...You would have to call the side 'Tasmania' as fans simply won't follow a relocated side with its traditional name, even if it was Collingwood\".<ref name=\"nla.gov.au\"/>\n\nIn April 1994 The Tasmanian Sports Minister, Peter Hodgman, spoke to the AFL about the possible introduction of a local team to the league and had raised the possibility of state funding.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article118112819 |title=AFL clubs oppose push for more sides |newspaper=[[The Canberra Times]] |volume=69 |issue=21,546 |location=Australian Capital Territory, Australia |date=13 April 1994 |accessdate=23 February 2018 |page=38 |via=National Library of Australia}}</ref>\n\nBetween 1994 and 1997 the bid was prepared for a Tasmanian team that involved the construction of a 30,000-capacity stadium at the [[Hobart Showground]]s in [[Glenorchy, Tasmania|Glenorchy]], at the cost of approximately $30 million.<ref name=\"newstadium\">{{cite web\n  | title = Ditch AFL bid: clubs\n  | publisher = Examiner \n  | date = 20 February 1998\n  | url = http://www.examiner.com.au/news/local/sport/general/ditch-afl-bid-clubs/1316425.aspx\n  | accessdate =20 April 2009}}</ref>\n\n===2008\u20132011: Tasmania beaten by Gold Coast and Western Sydney===\n{{Quote box\n | quote  = \"Tasmanians already watch AFL\"<br /><br />\n | source = '''[[Andrew Demetriou]]''', former AFL CEO and {{AFL Nor}} and {{AFL Haw}} player responding to questions regarding why Tasmania is not a priority in 2009.<ref>https://www.foxsports.com.au/afl/brisbane-lions-star-mitch-robinson-on-tasmanias-footy-crisis/news-story/752c43c07c7b1ee51ed3865209966c29</ref>\n | align  = right\n| width  = 35%\n }}\nThe AFL's continued rejection of the Tasmanian AFL team has raised significant controversy, with the [[Government of Australia]] launching a [[Senate of Australia|Senate]] inquiry in 2008 which [[AFL Commission]] CEO [[Andrew Demetriou]] and chairman [[Mike Fitzpatrick (footballer)|Mike Fitzpatrick]] both declined to attend.<ref name=\"themercury.com.au\">{{cite web|url=http://www.themercury.com.au/article/2009/03/28/63835_sport-news.html |title=Soccer could beat AFL |work=The Mercury |date=28 March 2009 |accessdate=24 October 2011}}</ref> At the enquiry, Tasmanian senator [[Kerry O'Brien (politician)|Kerry O'Brien]] brought into question the AFL's commitment to the game in Tasmania, and stated that he believed that with continued neglect, the popularity of [[Association football in Tasmania|soccer]] could overtake [[Australian rules football in Tasmania]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.themercury.com.au/article/2009/03/28/63835_sport-news.html|title=Soccer could beat AFL|date=28 March 2009}}</ref>  There are already more children playing soccer than Australian rules football in Tasmania.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.theage.com.au/news/soccer/soccer-on-rise-as-afl-treads-water/2006/12/31/1167500010371.html |title=Soccer on rise as AFL treads water |first= Tim |last=Colebatch|date=1 January 2007}}</ref>\n\nThe AFL argued that the New South Wales based participation numbers were in excess of that in Tasmania,<ref>[http://www.aph.gov.au/Senate/committee/rrat_ctte/afl_tasmania/report/e03.htm#anc2 Answers to questions: AFL \u2013 Mr Phil Martin (question 4)]</ref> furthering their argument that a team in Western Sydney was a higher priority. The Senate enquiry found that insurmountable cultural barriers would make such a move non-viable.<ref>[http://www.thewest.com.au/default.aspx?MenuID=4&ContentID=151020 AFL tells Senate to mind their own business]</ref>\n\nIn April 2008, Tasmania's former premier [[Paul Lennon]] revived the push for an AFL team by travelling to AFL House in [[Melbourne]] where the latest bid was officially launched. Although Lennon subsequently retired in May, the responsibility of steering the bid went to Economic Development Minister [[Paula Wriedt]]. Wriedt said Tasmania only made the case for a Tasmanian team, and were not trying to beat the Gold Coast or Greater Western Sydney to be the 17th or 18th club.<ref>{{cite web\n| url = http://www.theaustralian.news.com.au/story/0,25197,24029484-2722,00.html\n| title = Tasmania's bid for AFL team faltering\n| accessdate =14 August 2008\n| author = \n| date = 16 July 2008\n| publisher = The Australian\n}}</ref>\n\nAFL CEO Andrew Demetriou has said: \"They probably do deserve a team, we shouldn't dismiss the contribution that Tasmania has made to our game... They are absolutely entitled to put forward a proposal, but the commission has already decided where the 17th and 18th teams are going.\"<ref>{{cite web\n| url = http://www.canberratimes.com.au/news/local/news/general/afl-expansion-plans-yet-to-include-tassie/812001.aspx\n| title = AFL expansion plans yet to include Tassie\n| accessdate =14 August 2008\n| author = \n| date = 16 July 2008\n| publisher = The Canberra Times\n}}</ref>\n\nThe bid received a significant boost on 30 July 2008, with the announcement that the confectionery company [[Mars, Incorporated|Mars]] committed to being the proposed club's major sponsor.<ref>{{cite web\n| url = http://www.abc.net.au/news/stories/2008/08/01/2320914.htm\n| title = Tasmania given sweet boost to AFL bid\n| accessdate =14 August 2008\n| author = \n| date = 1 August 2008\n| publisher = ABC News\n}}</ref>\n\nSome media commentators have speculated that the AFL holds Tasmania open as a soft target for relocation of struggling Melbourne clubs. In 2010, there was increased speculation due to [[North Melbourne Football Club|North Melbourne]]'s commitment to move four home games annually to Hobart's [[Bellerive Oval]].<ref>[http://www.theroar.com.au/2010/07/29/dont-knock-north-for-looking-at-hobart/ Don't knock North for looking at Hobart], The Roar, Retrieved on 29 July 2010.</ref>\n\n=== 2011\u20132017: Off the AFL agenda and bare draft crop ===\nIn April 2014, AFL deputy chief executive [[Gillon McLachlan]] said he supported a \"single team representing Tasmania\". He stated Tasmania would be the next team to join the AFL, but that this would not happen for at least a decade.<ref>[http://www.examiner.com.au/story/2220931/no-tasmanian-afl-team-for-at-least-a-decade-says-mclachlan/ The Examiner \u2013 No Tasmanian AFL team for at least a decade, says McLachlan]</ref>\n\nIn 2016, the Garlick report confirmed that a stand-alone Tasmanian team would have to wait until current broadcast deals expire at the end of the 2022 season to enter the AFL.\n\nFor the [[2016 AFL draft|2016 AFL National Draft]] no Tasmanian players were drafted. The following year only one player was drafted.\n\nIn April 2017, the Tasmanian Government indicated its interest in relocating the [[Gold Coast Suns]] to Tasmania in the event the club collapses.<ref>[http://www.heraldsun.com.au/sport/afl/teams/gold-coast/tasmania-ready-to-swoop-for-the-gold-coast-suns-in-renewed-push-for-standalone-afl-team/news-story/85accae5a95877175cefd47ce9be6580 Tasmania launches new bid for AFL team, offering to relocate Gold Coast Suns]</ref>\n\nIn September 2017, the AFL awarded a licence for an [[AFL Women's]] team for the 2019 AFLW  season for a combined \"Tasmania-North Melbourne\" team. The submission for a licence was a joint project of the [[North Melbourne Football Club]] and the [[Government of Tasmania]].<ref name=\"ABC News - 27 September 2017 - AFLW: Tasmania-North Melbourne and Geelong win licences to field teams from 2019\">{{cite news|url=http://www.abc.net.au/news/2017-09-27/tasmania-nth-melb-geelong-win-new-aflw-licences-for-2019/8992508|title=AFLW: Tasmania-North Melbourne and Geelong win licences to field teams from 2019|date=27 September 2017|work=[[ABC News (Australia)]]|publisher=[[Australian Broadcasting Corporation]]|accessdate=27 September 2017}}</ref>\n\n=== Early 2018: AFL steering committee and A-League team bid ===\n\nIn early 2018, [[AFL Tasmania]] CEO Rob Auld resigned, and the following day Burnie and Devonport withdrew from the Tasmanian State League, citing lack of funding \nmaking them unable to field sides, thus leaving the competition without any team from North Western Tasmania.\n\nThe same week, AFL CEO [[Gillon McLachlan]] was quoted as saying he \u201chad a really clear plan for Tasmania\u201d; that week, the [[AFLX]] launch took place as well as an announcement that the Gold Coast Suns received $25 million in subsidies for 2017.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.afr.com/business/sport/the-afl-propped-up-gold-coast-suns-with-25m-after-sponsorship-woes-20180201-h0s15t|title=The AFL propped up on Gold Coast Suns with $25m after sponsorship woes|date=2018-02-04|work=Financial Review|access-date=2018-02-23|language=en-US}}</ref>\n\nOn 16 February 2018 the [[A-League]], a key rival of the AFL, announced it would expand its competition by two teams for the upcoming 2019-20 season and flagging that a Tasmanian bid was a key contender, though the bid was rejected in June 2018 after being cut from the [[Football Federation Australia|FFA]] shortlist.\n\nOn the 23 February 2018 during an interview on SEN, newly appointed AFL Tasmania CEO Trisha Squires did not have a position on whether Tasmania was better off with two fly-in-fly-out Victorian sides or its own side.<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.sen.com.au/news/2018/02/23/afl-tassie-boss-has-no-idea-whats-best-for-footy/|title=AFL Tassie boss has no idea what's best for footy|access-date=2018-02-23|language=en}}</ref> She also described talk of a standalone Tasmanian team as a \"distraction\".<ref name=\":2\" />\n\nSubsequent to these events, a steering committee was formed in March. On 3 July 2018, the committee delivered its findings.\n<ref>[https://www.examiner.com.au/story/5503002/tasmanian-fans-must-help-football-revival/?cs=96 Steering committee aims to unite Tasmanian football]</ref>\n\nMcLachlan announced the following recommendations to rebuild and unify Tasmanian football over the next three years:<ref name=Siri1>[http://amp.abc.net.au/article/9931164 AFL boss Gillon McLachlan to deliver Tasmanian football blueprint]</ref>\n\n*The AFL will invest an extra $1.4 million in Tasmania in 2019.\n*Create three regional administration hubs to help run community football.\n*Generate AFL affiliation with community leagues.\n*The TSL will remain the state's top-tier competition and continue to receive AFL funding.\n*Extend Tasmania's junior pathways from under-12s to under-18s with more opportunities to play in intrastate tournaments. Junior levies will also be removed.\n*A full-time under-18s Mariners program with Tasmania to compete in the TAC Cup from 2019.\n*Tasmania was granted a provisional licence to re-enter the VFL in 2021.\n*There will be greater investment in the talent pathway for women, with a girls\u2019 side to take part in TAC Cup from 2020.\n*A Tasmanian advisory board, made up of Tasmanians, will be set up to oversee the changes\n*All programs are to be re-branded under a name to be decided by the Tasmanian people.\n\nMclachlan also stated the success of these plans would help determine a potential date for a Tasmanian team to enter the AFL.<ref name=Siri1/>\n\n=== Late 2018: Political and social pressure and branding announcement  ===\nSeveral days later, [[Leader of the Opposition (Australia)|Opposition Leader]] [[Bill Shorten]] pledged $25 million in funding for a Tasmanian AFL team, contingent on the [[Australian Labor Party|Labor Party]] winning the [[2019 Australian federal election|2019 federal election]].<ref>[http://mobile.abc.net.au/news/2018-07-07/shortens-$25m-tasmanian-afl-pledge/9953384?pfmredir=sm Shorten's $25m Tasmanian AFL pledge welcomed, but doubts powerbrokers will be swayed]</ref>\n\nOn the 26 June 2018, Tasmanian Nationals Senator [[Steve Martin (Australian politician)|Steve Martin]] moved a motion calling for the AFL to commission business plans for the inclusion of a Tasmanian team in the men's and women's national league.<ref name=\":3\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.themercury.com.au/subscribe/news/1/?sourceCode=TMWEB_WRE170_a&dest=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.themercury.com.au%2Fnews%2Fpolitics%2Fnew-national-senator-steve-martin-makes-play-for-tassie-afl-team%2Fnews-story%2Fb2b253aa56459ed83dfe8c97cc8bde34&memtype=anonymous&mode=premium&nk=f8f5161f4e5b8ef324f383f77558e1a9-1555552592|title=Subscribe to The Mercury|website=www.themercury.com.au|access-date=2019-04-18}}</ref> At the time Senator Martin did so with the support of Coalition and Labor senators.<ref name=\":3\" />\n\nOn the 21 September 2018, Trisha Squires announced that representative Tasmanian football teams administered by [[AFL Tasmania]] would be known as the Tasmania Devils and would wear green, yellow and maroon.<ref name=\"THE DEVILS ARE BACK - AFL Tasmania\">{{Cite news|url=http://www.afltas.com.au/the-devils-are-back/|title=THE DEVILS ARE BACK - AFL Tasmania|date=2018-09-21|work=AFL Tasmania|access-date=2018-09-21|language=en-US}}</ref>\n\nOn 11 October 2018, [[Adrian Fletcher]] was named as the Tasmania Devils [[TAC Cup]] coach.\n\n===Early 2019: Guidelines set by AFL===\nOn 22 March 2019, Caroline Wilson broke the story that the AFL had set [[Will Hodgman]], Tasmanian Premier, guideline requirements to house an AFL team being:<ref name=\":4\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.theage.com.au/sport/afl/no-longer-if-but-when-push-grows-for-a-tasmanian-afl-team-20190322-p516mb.html|title='No longer if but when': Push grows for a Tasmanian AFL team|last=Wilson|first=Caroline|date=2019-03-22|website=The Age|language=en|access-date=2019-04-18}}</ref>\n\n* At least 50,000 members.\n* Up front capital of $40,000,000.\n* A unified Tasmanian football community.\n* AFL standard venues.\n* A minimum of 10 Tasmanian players in the AFL.\n* Designing a respectful exit strategy for current [[Fly-in fly-out|FIFO]] Victorian tenants [[North Melbourne Football Club|North Melbourne]] and [[Hawthorn Football Club|Hawthorn]].\n\nIt was noted that Tasmania had 90,000 members for the existing mainland AFL clubs in 2018.\n\n=== Late 2019: Taskforce formed ===\nIn mid-2019, a taskforce made up of people from the Australian business community was formed with the intent of gaining an AFL licence.<ref name=\":5\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.theage.com.au/sport/afl/riewoldt-to-join-tasmanian-afl-taskforce-20190625-p52171.html|title=Riewoldt to join Tasmanian AFL taskforce|last=Ryan|first=Peter|date=2019-06-25|website=The Age|language=en|access-date=2019-08-20}}</ref> The taskforce is being chaired by [[Brett Godfrey]].<ref name=\":5\" />\n\nThese taskforce members were:<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.examiner.com.au/story/6205390/task-force-meet-for-first-time/|title=Task-force meet for first time|last=Partridge|first=Josh|date=2019-06-07|website=The Examiner|language=en|access-date=2019-08-20}}</ref>\n\n* [[Brett Godfrey]] (chair)\n* Errol Stewart\n* Grant O'Brien\n* Julie Kay\n* Paul Eriksson\n* James Henderson\n\nThe [[Tourism Industry Council of Tasmania]] also backed the push for a stand alone Tasmanian AFL team, saying it would have substantial positive impacts on multiple facets of the state's economy, and reiterated that \"A Tasmanian AFL team [should] play out of both the North and South of the state, with a relatively even number of games in both Hobart and Launceston each year...We believe this principle must be accepted as fundamental to further discussion about an AFL team in Tasmania to completely destruct any perceptions of a 'Southern' or 'Northern' team...Rather than seeing this as a challenge in the formation of the team, we see it as one of its strengths in being a unifying force within the state and maximising the resources of all regions.\" <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.examiner.com.au/story/6296117/states-peak-tourism-body-enters-tasmanian-afl-team-debate/|title=State's peak tourism body enters Tasmanian AFL team debate|last=Inglis|first=Rob|date=2019-07-27|website=The Examiner|language=en|access-date=2019-08-20}}</ref>'\n\nOn 23 August 2019, Caroline Wilson reported that the taskforce would be applying for a provisional AFL licence before the end of the year.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.theage.com.au/sport/afl/tasmania-set-to-apply-for-a-provisional-afl-licence-20190823-p52k4n.html|title=Tasmania set to apply for a provisional AFL licence|last=Wilson|first=Caroline|date=2019-08-23|website=The Age|language=en|access-date=2019-08-27}}</ref> The taskforce has aimed to enter the competition in 2025, when the extended broadcast rights deal expires. Plans to build a new stadium and training facility at Hobart's Macquarie Point were also revealed, while the VFL team's entry could also be delayed to 2022 to develop local talent. On the 8 November 2019 the Taskforce run petition surpassed 60,000 pledges in support of a Tasmanian AFL team.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.themercury.com.au/news/tasmania-to-cut-apron-strings-by-joining-the-afl-as-its-first-sporting-goal/news-story/5f5be82ad9931347b38eff23fe68ef20|title=Tasmania to cut apron strings by joining the AFL as its first sporting goal|last=Stubbs|first=Brett|date=8 November 2019|website=themercury.com.au|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\n=== 2020: Coronavirus impact ===\n\nDue to the [[2019-20 coronavirus pandemic]], Collingwood President Eddie McGuire has stated it could take ten years for the AFL and its clubs to recover, likely pushing back Tasmania's AFL team aspirations in the short to medium term. <ref> [https://www.theadvocate.com.au/story/6688736/tassie-afl-team-hopes-fading-says-eddie-mcguire/ Tasmania to wait for AFL hopes] </ref> In this regard, Nick Riewoldt stated Tasmania still has an opportunity to contribute to the game and its recovery.\n\nWhile Tasmanian AFL Taskforce chairman Brett Godfrey has promised to continue pushing Tasmania's case at the appropriate time, he remains optimistic about a 2025 entry date, and has also expressed interest in a Tasmanian team entering the competition earlier in the event an existing AFL club collapses as a result of the crisis.\n\nSince the crisis has effectively forced Tasmania to close its borders, the prospect of Hawthorn and North Melbourne moving their Tasmanian games to Melbourne has been raised; a decision on this is yet to be finalised, and the 2020 season was suspended on March 22.\n\n== Honour board ==\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|+\n! colspan=\"8\" |Tasmania Devils Honour Board\n|-\n! colspan=\"8\" |[[NAB League]]\n|-\n!Year\n!Position\n!W-L-D\n!%\n!Coach\n!Captain\n!Best & Fairest\n!Leading Goal Kicker\n|-\n|[[2019 NAB League season|2019]]\n|14/18 (12/13)\n|4-11-0, lost Wildcard Final\n|80\n|[[Adrian Fletcher]]<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.examiner.com.au/story/5698802/fletcher-to-drive-devils-full-time-tac-cup-return/|title=Fletcher to drive Devils' full-time TAC Cup return|last=Martin|first=Corey|date=2018-10-12|work=The Examiner|access-date=2018-10-24|language=en}}</ref>\n|Nic Baker<br />Jared Dakin<br />Oliver Davis\n|\n|Jackson Callow (24)<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://websites.sportstg.com/comp_info.cgi?c=1-3020-0-518307-0&a=STATS|title=Season Statistics for 2019 NAB League|website=SportsTG|language=en|access-date=2019-06-07}}</ref>\n|-\n|2020\n|\n|\n|\n|Cameron Joyce\n|\n|\n|\n|}\n\n== VFL teams ==\n\n=== Tasmanian Devils Football Club (2001 \u2013 2008) ===\n{{main|Tasmanian Devils Football Club}}\nIn 2001 the [[Tasmanian Devils Football Club]] was formed and competed in the [[Victorian Football League]] until 2008.\n\nDuring the 1990s, Tasmania had shown strong interest in joining the AFL and after rejected bids in 1995 and 1997 the [[Australian Football League]] instigated the formation a Tasmanian team for the newly re-constructed [[Victorian Football League]]. The Tasmanian Devils Football Club formed in 2001 and was admitted into the VFL in its inaugural season the same year. The AFL continues to own the club.\n\nThe nickname \"Devils\" was chosen as the moniker for the club after the tenacious marsupial predator the [[Tasmanian devil]] which is indigenous to the island of Tasmania. The club colours green, red, gold (and black) were inspired by the original [[Interstate matches in Australian rules football|State of Origin]] \"map\" guernsey and are also Tasmania's sporting colours.\n\nThe Devils established home grounds in both [[Hobart]] and [[Launceston, Tasmania|Launceston]] to deal with the long-standing north-south rivalry. Originally northern home games were played at Ulverstone, Devonport, Burnie and at Launceston's [[Aurora Stadium]] while [[North Hobart Oval]] hosted games in the south. At the end of the 2005 season the team moved from North Hobart Oval to [[Bellerive Oval]] for home games in the south and began playing all northern home games at Aurora Stadium.\n\n2001 and 2002 brought mediocre results but, under the direction of coach [[Matthew Armstrong (Australian footballer)|Matthew Armstrong]], the Devils made the finals for the first time in 2003, finishing a respectable third. The 2004 and 2005 seasons saw the Devils again making the finals.\n\nAt the start of the 2006 season the Devils and the [[Australian Football League]]'s [[North Melbourne Football Club]] began a [[Australian Football League reserves affiliations|partial alignment]], allowing North Melbourne listed players to play for Tasmania when not selected in the seniors, and arrangement which lasted from 2006 until 2007. This was unpopular among local fans, significantly harming the popularity of the club; and the season proved to be a disappointment on-field, with the Devils finishing ninth and missing the finals.<ref name=\"wade1\">{{cite news|newspaper=The Mercury|location=Hobart, TAS|title=The power and the passion: Scott Wade reflects on a career at the coalface of Tasmanian football|date=12 March 2016|accessdate=31 July 2016|url=http://www.themercury.com.au/sport/afl/the-power-and-the-passion-scott-wade-reflects-on-a-career-at-the-coalface-of-tasmanian-football/news-story/76cf3fb235222e7335338bc1a8b6dbb4}}</ref><ref name=\"wade2\">{{cite web|title=AFL Tasmania chief Scott Wade's resignation was a 'mutual decision', AFL says|url=http://www.abc.net.au/news/2016-03-09/afl-tasmania-chief-scott-wade-quits/7229750|date=9 March 2016|author=Scott Rollinson|publisher=Australian Broadcasting Corporation}}</ref> During the 2006 season, Armstrong stepped down as coach due to internal pressure from the playing group, ending his six-year term as Devils coach. [[North Hobart Football Club|North Hobart]] premiership coach and former Devil [[Brendon Bolton]] was made stand in coach for the remainder of the year.<ref name=\"Tasmania Devils history\">[http://australianfootball.com/clubs/info/Tasmania/249 Tasmania Devils history]</ref>\n\nTasmanian and former [[Sydney Swans|Sydney Swan]] [[Daryn Cresswell]] was named coach of the club for 2007 after a successful career as an assistant coach at [[Geelong Football Club|Geelong]] and the [[Brisbane Lions]]; however, hampered in part by Cresswell's off-field issues which included a gambling addiction and eventual fraud conviction, the club finished wooden spooners both seasons he coached the team, winning only six of a total 34 games.<ref name=\"wade1\" /><ref name=\"wade2\" />\n\nAt the end of the 2008 season, AFL Tasmania decided to withdraw the Devils from the VFL competition in favour of restarting a new Tasmanian league encompassing the entire state.<ref name=\"Tasmania Devils history\"/>\n\n=== Tasmania Devils (2021 or 2022) ===\nThe AFL plans on fielding a Tasmanian team in the Victorian Football League in 2021 or 2022 as a potential precursor to a team entering the Australian Football League.\n\n== Victorian AFL clubs in Tasmania ==\nAs Tasmania is the last Australian state to house an AFL team, and is also a heartland state of the code (unlike New South Wales and Queensland), the league has often used the state for Melbourne-based clubs to host games in Tasmania subsidised by local and the Tasmanian state governments. Both of the current deals with Hawthorn and North Melbourne will expire in 2021.<ref>[https://www.abc.net.au/news/2019-03-20/tasmanian-afl-dream-alive-after-gil-mclachlan-quip/10915680 Are all signs pointing to a Tasmanian AFL team?]</ref>\n\n*[[Fitzroy Football Club|Fitzroy]] (1991\u20131992)\n*[[Hawthorn Football Club|Hawthorn]] (2001\u2013present)\n*[[St Kilda Football Club|St Kilda]] (2003\u20132006)\n*[[North Melbourne Football Club|North Melbourne]] (2012\u2013present)\n\n== Supporters ==\n{| class=\"wikitable\" align=\"right\" style=\"font-size: 80%\"\n! colspan=\"3\" |Guernsey sponsors\n|-\n!Period\n!Front sponsor\n!Back sponsor\n|-\n!2019\n| AFL Tasmania + NAB || Cripps Nubake\n|}\nTasmanian news website and newspaper ''[[The Mercury (Hobart)|The Mercury]]'' has been a vocal supporter of the bid.<ref>{{cite news\n| url = http://www.news.com.au/mercury/story/0,22884,23355142-5016971,00.html\n| title = Our crusade to end Tassie's footy snub\n| accessdate =14 August 2008\n| date = 11 March 2008\n| publisher = The Mercury\n|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080511164906/http://www.news.com.au/mercury/story/0,22884,23355142-5016971,00.html\n|archivedate=11 May 2008\n| quote = ''And today ... the Mercury launches its season-long campaign, Tasmania \u2013 It's Time, to reignite the push for a Tasmanian team in the AFL.''\n}}</ref><ref>[http://www.themercury.com.au/sport/afl/cmon-tassie-we-need-a-team-effort/story-fnj4f7h7-1226862240976 The Mercury \u2013 C\u2019mon Tassie, we need a team effort]</ref>\n[[Kevin Sheedy (Australian footballer)|Kevin Sheedy]] has argued that Tasmania is not too small for an AFL team. He stated that population is irrelevant, and that a Tasmanian side could draw support from abroad in a similar way to the [[Green Bay Packers]].<ref name=\":0\">[http://www.abc.net.au/news/stories/2007/06/14/1951493.htm Tasmania not too small for an AFL team: Sheedy]</ref> In 2008 Tasmanian bank [[MyState Financial]] offered $300,000 over three years in sponsorship of a team.<ref name=\":1\">{{cite news|title=Tas bid gains momentum|url=http://www.theadvocate.com.au/story/672352/tas-bid-gains-momentum/|accessdate=18 January 2015|publisher=The Advocate|date=26 August 2008}}</ref>\n\n=== Government supporters ===\n* Tasmanian Government \u2013 $19,000,000 over 5 years (2015 deal with [[Hawthorn Football Club|Hawthorn]])<ref>{{Cite web|title = Tasmanian Government signs new five-year deal with Hawthorn|url = http://www.themercury.com.au/sport/afl/tasmanian-government-signs-new-five-year-deal-with-hawthorn/story-fnj4f7h7-1227465237561|accessdate = 2015-09-28}}</ref>\n* Tasmanian Government \u2013 $2,500,000 over 5 years (2017 deal with {{AFL Nor}} Women's team)<ref>http://www.abc.net.au/news/2017-09-27/tassie-kangaroos-tasmanias-new-afl-team/8994214</ref>\n* Hobart City Council \u2013 $600,000 over 2 years (2014 deal with [[North Melbourne Football Club|North Melbourne]])<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.abc.net.au/news/2014-08-26/north-melbourne-deal-seals-three-games-a-year-in-hobart/5696024|title=North Melbourne deal seals three AFL games a year in Hobart|website=ABC News|accessdate=2015-09-28}}</ref>\n* Spirit of Tasmania \u2013 $1,800,000 over 3 years (2016 deal with North Melbourne)<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.northweststar.com.au/story/3737927/north-melbourne-set-to-beat-hawthorn-to-tasmanian-academy/?cs=12|title=North Melbourne set to beat Hawthorn to Tasmanian academy|last=Wilson|first=Caroline|date=2016-02-18|work=The North West Star|access-date=2018-02-23|language=en}}</ref>\n\n=== Corporate support ===\n* [[Mars, Incorporated|MARS]] \u2013 $4,000,000 over three years (2008 proposal)<ref>{{Cite news|url = http://www.heraldsun.com.au/sport/afl/tassie-planets-align/story-e6frf9jf-1111117073738|title = Tasmanian AFL team secures major sponsor|date =31 July 2008 |accessdate = 4 October 2015|work= Herald Sun |publisher = |last = Pierik|first = Jon }}</ref>\n* MyState Financial \u2013 $300,000 (2008 proposal)<ref name=\":1\" />\n\n=== Media supporters ===\n* Kevin Sheedy<ref name=\":0\"/>\n* Tim Lane<ref>{{Cite web|url = http://www.themercury.com.au/news/tasmania/tasmania-should-cash-in-on-support-for-afl-team-says-leading-football-commentator-tim-lane/story-fnj4f7k1-1227432894273|title = Tasmania should cash in on support for AFL team, says leading football commentator Tim Lane|date = 8 July 2015|accessdate = |website = |publisher = |last = THOMAS-WILSON|first = SIMEON}}</ref>\n* Mitch Robinson\n* Nick Riewoldt\n* Matthew Richardson\n* Andy Maher\n* Caroline Wilson\n* Brian Carlton\n* Jack Riewoldt\n\n== Venues and travel==\n{{multiple image\n| align    = right\n| image1   = Bellerive oval hobart.jpg\n| width1   = 220\n| alt1     = \n| image2   = Hawthorn v Western Bulldogs - &nbsp;31st&nbsp;May&nbsp;2008 181.jpg\n| width2   = 195\n| alt2     = \n| footer   = Left: Bellerive Oval would serve as the club's home ground in Hobart.<br/>Right: Tasmania's potential second ground, UTAS Stadium (York Park) in Launceston.\n}}\nDue to the population split of Tasmania between Hobart and Launceston it has been proposed that a future Tasmania club use two home grounds Launceston and Hobart which are approximately 200&nbsp;km apart.\n\nIt has often been suggested that the home games could be split between the two population centres with Hobart hosting six games a year and Launceston hosting five.\n\n=== Hobart ===\nHobart is Tasmania's largest city with a population around 230,000 which is comparable to [[City of Greater Geelong|Greater Geelong]]. The record crowd for an Australian rules game in Hobart was 24,968 for the 1979 TANFL Grand Final at [[North Hobart Oval]]. In August 2019 a Tasmanian Parliamentary Committee heard from the Tasmanian Football Board regarding a new purpose built stadium at Macquarie Point as part of a bid for an AFL team.<ref>https://www.themercury.com.au/sport/local-sport/macquarie-point-multipurpose-stadium-would-be-ideal-for-tasmanian-afl-team-parliamentary-committee-hears/news-story/664be9ce62cd66c10efb611bab22a642</ref>\n\n=== Launceston ===\nLaunceston is the second largest city in Tasmania housing nearly 90,000 people which is comparable in population to the [[Division of Fremantle|Federal Division of Fremantle]]. The northern half of Tasmania is home to half the states population. It is the economic centre of Northern Tasmania. The record crowd for an Australian rules game in Launceston was 20,971 at York Park an AFL minor round fixture in 2006.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|2}}\n\n==External links==\n* [https://archive.today/20121231001808/http://www.tassiefootyteam.com.au/ Tasmanian Government official bid website]\n\n{{AFL}}\n{{Aussie Rules in Tasmania}}\n{{TAC Cup}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Tasmanian Afl Bid}}\n[[Category:Proposed VFL/AFL clubs]]\n[[Category:Australian rules football in Tasmania]]\n", "name_user": "David Stewart", "label": "safe", "comment": "TM application for logo", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Tasmanian_AFL_bid"}
{"title_page": "Pravin Joshi", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2019}}\n{{short description|Indian actor}}\n\n{{Infobox person\n| name               = Pravin Joshi\n| image              = \n| image_size         = 180px\n| birth_date         = {{birth date |df=y|1934|1|1}}\n| birth_place        = \n| death_date         = {{Death date and age|df=y|1979|1|19|1934|1|1}}\n| death_place        = \n| occupation         = Actor, director, playwright\n| spouse             = [[Sarita Joshi]]\n| children           = [[Purbi Joshi ]], [[Ketki Dave]]\n| parents            = \n}}\n'''Pravin Joshi''' (1 January 1934 \u2013 19 January 1979) was an Indian stage actor and director. He was a leading figure of the commercial [[Gujarati theatre]] in the 1960\u201370s.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.sahapedia.org/pravin-joshi|title=Pravin Joshi|date=12 January 2018|website=Sahapedia|access-date=2 January 2019}}</ref><ref name=\":055\" />\n\n==Biography==\nPravin Joshi was one of the most dynamic figures of the contemporary Gujarati Stage. He participated in the one-act play competitions organised by the [[Bharatiya Vidya Bhavan]] in Bombay (now Mumbai) in the mid-1950s where he was received attention. He crossed over naturally from the arena inter-collegiate competitions to the professional Gujarati Theatre. He joined the [[Indian National Theatre]] (INT) in 1956 was trained under Damu Jhaveri.<ref name=\"Hiralaxmi\">{{cite book |last1=Shah Dhanya Gurjari Kendra |first1=Hiralaxmi Navanitbhai |title=Gujarat |publisher=Gujarat Vishvakosh Trust |page=486 |url=https://books.google.com.au/books?id=g4oMAQAAMAAJ&q=%22Pravin+Joshi%22&dq=%22Pravin+Joshi%22&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjM1YHqit7fAhUBu7wKHdrnB9cQ6AEIQDAE |accessdate=8 January 2019}}</ref> For the INT he played triple role of translator, actor and director.\n\nHe was trained at the [[Royal Academy of Dramatic Art]], London.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Champaklal|first=Mahesh|author-link=Mahesh Champaklal|date=April 2018|title=\u0ab0\u0a82\u0a97\u0ab0\u0abe\u0a9c\u0ab5\u0ac0 \u0aaa\u0acd\u0ab0\u0ab5\u0ac0\u0aa3 \u0a9c\u0acb\u0ab7\u0ac0|trans-title=Pravin Joshi \u2013 The King of Theatre|url=http://opinionmagazine.co.uk/details/3645/rangraajavee-pravin-joshi|journal=\u0ab5\u0abf\u0ab6\u0acd\u0ab5\u0ab5\u0abf\u0ab9\u0abe\u0ab0 [Vishwavihar]|language=gu|volume=18|issue=7|pages=4\u20137|via=Opinion Magazine}}</ref>\n\nHe had traveled abroad to imbibe the best of world theatre and to his last breath he shared his knowledge of drama with others. He toured Gujarat - Saurashtra with the INT dramas and held the audiences spellbound with these plays.  \n\nHis about 25 plays produced under the INT introduced sophistication in the Gujarati theatre.<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com.au/books?id=uwFlAAAAMAAJ&q=%22Pravin+Joshi%22&dq=%22Pravin+Joshi%22&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjim9bNlN7fAhWLy7wKHSevAHo4ChDoAQgtMAE|title=Rasa: Theatre and cinema|last1=Mukherjee|first1=Bimal|last2=Kothari|first2=Sunil|last3=Lal|first3=Ananda|last4=Das Gupta|first4=Chidananda|date=1995|publisher=Anamika Kala Sangam|page=128|accessdate=8 January 2019}}</ref> He directed and acted in several successful adaptations including ''Mogarana Sap'' (Snake in the Jasmine, 1963, adapted from [[Frederick Knott]]'s ''Dial M for Murder''), ''Manju Manju'' (1965, adapted from [[Jean Kerr]]'s ''[[Mary, Mary (play)|Mary Mary]]''), ''Chandarvo'' (Colourful Canopy, 1966, from ''Merry-go-round'' by [[Albert Maltz]] and George Sklar), ''Santu Rangili'' (Enchanting Santu, 1974, adapted from [[George Bernard Shaw]]'s ''[[Pygmalion (play)|Pygmalion]]'' by [[Madhu Rye]]), ''Mosam Chhalake'' (Pleasant Times, 1978, adapted from [[Bernard Slade]]'s ''[[Same Time, Next Year (play)|Same Time, Next Year]]''),<ref name=\":055\" /> ''Sharat'' (A Bet, adapted from [[Friedrich D\u00fcrrenmatt]]'s [[The Visit (play)|''The Visit'']]) and ''Khelando'' (Player, adapted from [[Anthony Shaffer (writer)|Anthony Shaffer]]'s [[Sleuth (play)|''Sleuth'']]). His other successful plays as a director include ''Moti Verana Chokma'' and ''Kumarni Agashi'' (Kumar's Terrace, by Madhu Rye)''.''<ref name=\"Ahuja\">{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com.au/books?id=YDSHSkYp6M0C&q=%22Pravin+Joshi%22&dq=%22Pravin+Joshi%22&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwj6mrrLi97fAhUR97wKHR75DmM4ChDoAQhPMAk|title=Contemporary Theatre of India: An Overview|last1=Ahuja|first1=Chaman|date=2012|publisher=National Book Trust|isbn=9788123764917|location=India|accessdate=8 January 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn most of the plays he acted alongside [[Sarita Joshi]], whom he later married.<ref name=\":055\">{{Cite book|url=http://www.oxfordreference.com/view/10.1093/acref/9780195644463.001.0001/acref-9780195644463-e-0239#|title=Oxford Companion to Indian Theatre|last=Baradi|first=Hasmukh |publisher=Oxford University Press|year=2004|isbn=9780195644463|editor-last=Lal|editor-first=Ananda|location=|pages=|language=en|chapter=Joshi, Pravin (1936\u201380) and Sarita (1941\u2013\u2002): leading Gujarati husband-and-wife acting duo.|doi=10.1093/acref/9780195644463.001.0001|via=Oxford Reference}} {{subscription required}}</ref><ref name=\"screen\">{{cite web|url=http://www.screenindia.com/old/20020322/tvcov.html|title=Twining|date=22 March 2002|work=Screen|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080302060144/http://www.screenindia.com/old/20020322/tvcov.html|archivedate=2 March 2008|url-status=dead|accessdate=26 August 2009|df=dmy-all}}</ref> Their daughters [[Ketki Dave]] and [[Purbi Joshi]] are also actresses.\n\nPravin Joshi died in an accident on 19th January 1979.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n==Plays==\n{{columns-list|colwidth=40em|*''Kadam Milake Chalo'' (1958)\n*''Kaumar Asambhavam'' (1961)\n*''Meen Pyasi'' (1961)\n*''Mogarana Saap'' (1962)<ref name=\"Opinion\">{{cite web |last1=\u0a9a\u0a82\u0aaa\u0a95\u0ab2\u0abe\u0ab2 |first1=\u0aae\u0ab9\u0ac7\u0ab6 |title=\u0ab0\u0a82\u0a97\u0ab0\u0abe\u0a9c\u0ab5\u0ac0 \u0aaa\u0acd\u0ab0\u0ab5\u0ac0\u0aa3 \u0a9c\u0acb\u0ab7\u0ac0 |url=http://opinionmagazine.co.uk/details/3645/rangraajavee-pravin-joshi |website=Opinion Magazine |accessdate=1 January 2019 |language=Gujarati |date=14 July 2018}}</ref>''\n*''Shyam Gulab'' (1963)\n*''Koino Ladkvayo'' (1964)\n*''Manju Manju'' (1965)\n*''Manas Name Karagar'' (1966)\n*''Chandarvo'' (1966)\n*''Ane Indrajit'' (1967) \n*''Saptapadi'' (1967)\n*''Dhummas'' (1968)<ref>{{cite book |last1=Usman |first1=Yasser |title=Rajesh Khanna: The Untold Story of India\u2019s First Superstar |date=2014 |publisher=Penguin UK |isbn=9789351188759 |url=https://books.google.com.au/books?id=xhK0BQAAQBAJ&pg=PT49&dq=%22Pravin+Joshi%22&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjM1YHqit7fAhUBu7wKHdrnB9cQ6AEIKjAA#v=onepage&q=%22Pravin%20Joshi%22&f=false |accessdate=8 January 2019}}</ref>''\n*''AganKhel'' (1968)\n*''Moti Verana Chokma'' (1969)\n*''Sagpanna Phul'' (1970)\n*''Sapnana Vavetar'' (1971)\n*''Chor Bajar'' (1972)\n*''Kumarni Agashi'' (1972)\n*''Santu Rangili'' (1973)\n*''Salgya Surajmukhi'' (1974)\n*''Saybo Gulabno Chod''\n*''Sharat'' (1975)\n*''Vaishakhi Koyal'' (1976)\n*''Khelando'' (1976)\n*''Thank You Mr.Glad'' (1977)\n*''Mausam Chhalake'' (1978)}}\n\n== Filmography ==\n\n* ''Kumkum Pagla'' (1972)\n* ''Aakrant'' (1973)\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{IMDb name}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Joshi, Pravin}}\n[[Category:Indian male stage actors]]\n[[Category:Indian theatre directors]]\n[[Category:Indian male dramatists and playwrights]]\n[[Category:Indian male musical theatre actors]]\n[[Category:Gujarati theatre]]\n[[Category:20th-century Indian dramatists and playwrights]]\n[[Category:20th-century Indian male actors]]\n[[Category:People from Mumbai]]\n[[Category:1934 births]]\n[[Category:1979 deaths]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2019}}\n{{short description|Indian actor}}\n\n{{Infobox person\n| name               = Pravin Joshi\n| image              = \n| image_size         = 180px\n| birth_date         = {{birth date |df=y|1934|1|1}}\n| birth_place        = \n| death_date         = {{Death date and age|df=y|1979|1|19|1934|1|1}}\n| death_place        = \n| occupation         = Actor, director, playwright\n| spouse             = [[Sarita Joshi]]\n| children           = [[Purbi Joshi ]], [[Ketki Dave]]\n| parents            = \n}}\n'''Pravin Joshi''' (1 January 1934 \u2013 19 January 1979) was an Indian stage actor and director. He was a leading figure of the commercial [[Gujarati theatre]] in the 1960\u201370s.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.sahapedia.org/pravin-joshi|title=Pravin Joshi|date=12 January 2018|website=Sahapedia|access-date=2 January 2019}}</ref><ref name=\":055\" />\n\n==Biography==\nPravin Joshi was one of the most dynamic figures of the contemporary Gujarati Stage. He participated in the one-act play competitions organised by the [[Bharatiya Vidya Bhavan]] in Bombay (now Mumbai) in the mid-1950s where he was received attention. He crossed over naturally from the arena inter-collegiate competitions to the professional Gujarati Theatre. He joined the [[Indian National Theatre]] (INT) in 1956 was trained under Damu Jhaveri.<ref name=\"Hiralaxmi\">{{cite book |last1=Shah Dhanya Gurjari Kendra |first1=Hiralaxmi Navanitbhai |title=Gujarat |publisher=Gujarat Vishvakosh Trust |page=486 |url=https://books.google.com.au/books?id=g4oMAQAAMAAJ&q=%22Pravin+Joshi%22&dq=%22Pravin+Joshi%22&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjM1YHqit7fAhUBu7wKHdrnB9cQ6AEIQDAE |accessdate=8 January 2019}}</ref> For the INT he played triple role of translator, actor and director.\n\nPravin Joshi was trained at the [[Royal Academy of Dramatic Art]], London.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Champaklal|first=Mahesh|author-link=Mahesh Champaklal|date=April 2018|title=\u0ab0\u0a82\u0a97\u0ab0\u0abe\u0a9c\u0ab5\u0ac0 \u0aaa\u0acd\u0ab0\u0ab5\u0ac0\u0aa3 \u0a9c\u0acb\u0ab7\u0ac0|trans-title=Pravin Joshi \u2013 The King of Theatre|url=http://opinionmagazine.co.uk/details/3645/rangraajavee-pravin-joshi|journal=\u0ab5\u0abf\u0ab6\u0acd\u0ab5\u0ab5\u0abf\u0ab9\u0abe\u0ab0 [Vishwavihar]|language=gu|volume=18|issue=7|pages=4\u20137|via=Opinion Magazine}}</ref>\n\nPravin Joshi had traveled abroad to imbibe the best of world theatre and to his last breath he shared his knowledge of drama with others. He toured Gujarat - Saurashtra with the INT dramas and held the audiences spellbound with these plays.  \n\nHis about 25 plays produced under the INT introduced sophistication in the Gujarati theatre.<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com.au/books?id=uwFlAAAAMAAJ&q=%22Pravin+Joshi%22&dq=%22Pravin+Joshi%22&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjim9bNlN7fAhWLy7wKHSevAHo4ChDoAQgtMAE|title=Rasa: Theatre and cinema|last1=Mukherjee|first1=Bimal|last2=Kothari|first2=Sunil|last3=Lal|first3=Ananda|last4=Das Gupta|first4=Chidananda|date=1995|publisher=Anamika Kala Sangam|page=128|accessdate=8 January 2019}}</ref> He directed and acted in several successful adaptations including ''Mogarana Sap'' (Snake in the Jasmine, 1963, adapted from [[Frederick Knott]]'s ''Dial M for Murder''), ''Manju Manju'' (1965, adapted from [[Jean Kerr]]'s ''[[Mary, Mary (play)|Mary Mary]]''), ''Chandarvo'' (Colourful Canopy, 1966, from ''Merry-go-round'' by [[Albert Maltz]] and George Sklar), ''Santu Rangili'' (Enchanting Santu, 1974, adapted from [[George Bernard Shaw]]'s ''[[Pygmalion (play)|Pygmalion]]'' by [[Madhu Rye]]), ''Mosam Chhalake'' (Pleasant Times, 1978, adapted from [[Bernard Slade]]'s ''[[Same Time, Next Year (play)|Same Time, Next Year]]''),<ref name=\":055\" /> ''Sharat'' (A Bet, adapted from [[Friedrich D\u00fcrrenmatt]]'s [[The Visit (play)|''The Visit'']]) and ''Khelando'' (Player, adapted from [[Anthony Shaffer (writer)|Anthony Shaffer]]'s [[Sleuth (play)|''Sleuth'']]). His other successful plays as a director include ''Moti Verana Chokma'' and ''Kumarni Agashi'' (Kumar's Terrace, by Madhu Rye)''.''<ref name=\"Ahuja\">{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com.au/books?id=YDSHSkYp6M0C&q=%22Pravin+Joshi%22&dq=%22Pravin+Joshi%22&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwj6mrrLi97fAhUR97wKHR75DmM4ChDoAQhPMAk|title=Contemporary Theatre of India: An Overview|last1=Ahuja|first1=Chaman|date=2012|publisher=National Book Trust|isbn=9788123764917|location=India|accessdate=8 January 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn most of the plays he acted alongside [[Sarita Joshi]], whom he later married.<ref name=\":055\">{{Cite book|url=http://www.oxfordreference.com/view/10.1093/acref/9780195644463.001.0001/acref-9780195644463-e-0239#|title=Oxford Companion to Indian Theatre|last=Baradi|first=Hasmukh |publisher=Oxford University Press|year=2004|isbn=9780195644463|editor-last=Lal|editor-first=Ananda|location=|pages=|language=en|chapter=Joshi, Pravin (1936\u201380) and Sarita (1941\u2013\u2002): leading Gujarati husband-and-wife acting duo.|doi=10.1093/acref/9780195644463.001.0001|via=Oxford Reference}} {{subscription required}}</ref><ref name=\"screen\">{{cite web|url=http://www.screenindia.com/old/20020322/tvcov.html|title=Twining|date=22 March 2002|work=Screen|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080302060144/http://www.screenindia.com/old/20020322/tvcov.html|archivedate=2 March 2008|url-status=dead|accessdate=26 August 2009|df=dmy-all}}</ref> Their daughters [[Ketki Dave]] and [[Purbi Joshi]] are also actresses.\n\nPravin Joshi died in an accident on 19th January 1979.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n==Plays==\n{{columns-list|colwidth=40em|*''Kadam Milake Chalo'' (1958)\n*''Kaumar Asambhavam'' (1961)\n*''Meen Pyasi'' (1961)\n*''Mogarana Saap'' (1962)<ref name=\"Opinion\">{{cite web |last1=\u0a9a\u0a82\u0aaa\u0a95\u0ab2\u0abe\u0ab2 |first1=\u0aae\u0ab9\u0ac7\u0ab6 |title=\u0ab0\u0a82\u0a97\u0ab0\u0abe\u0a9c\u0ab5\u0ac0 \u0aaa\u0acd\u0ab0\u0ab5\u0ac0\u0aa3 \u0a9c\u0acb\u0ab7\u0ac0 |url=http://opinionmagazine.co.uk/details/3645/rangraajavee-pravin-joshi |website=Opinion Magazine |accessdate=1 January 2019 |language=Gujarati |date=14 July 2018}}</ref>''\n*''Shyam Gulab'' (1963)\n*''Koino Ladkvayo'' (1964)\n*''Manju Manju'' (1965)\n*''Manas Name Karagar'' (1966)\n*''Chandarvo'' (1966)\n*''Ane Indrajit'' (1967) \n*''Saptapadi'' (1967)\n*''Dhummas'' (1968)<ref>{{cite book |last1=Usman |first1=Yasser |title=Rajesh Khanna: The Untold Story of India\u2019s First Superstar |date=2014 |publisher=Penguin UK |isbn=9789351188759 |url=https://books.google.com.au/books?id=xhK0BQAAQBAJ&pg=PT49&dq=%22Pravin+Joshi%22&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjM1YHqit7fAhUBu7wKHdrnB9cQ6AEIKjAA#v=onepage&q=%22Pravin%20Joshi%22&f=false |accessdate=8 January 2019}}</ref>''\n*''AganKhel'' (1968)\n*''Moti Verana Chokma'' (1969)\n*''Sagpanna Phul'' (1970)\n*''Sapnana Vavetar'' (1971)\n*''Chor Bajar'' (1972)\n*''Kumarni Agashi'' (1972)\n*''Santu Rangili'' (1973)\n*''Salgya Surajmukhi'' (1974)\n*''Saybo Gulabno Chod''\n*''Sharat'' (1975)\n*''Vaishakhi Koyal'' (1976)\n*''Khelando'' (1976)\n*''Thank You Mr.Glad'' (1977)\n*''Mausam Chhalake'' (1978)}}\n\n== Filmography ==\n\n* ''Kumkum Pagla'' (1972)\n* ''Aakrant'' (1973)\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{IMDb name}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Joshi, Pravin}}\n[[Category:Indian male stage actors]]\n[[Category:Indian theatre directors]]\n[[Category:Indian male dramatists and playwrights]]\n[[Category:Indian male musical theatre actors]]\n[[Category:Gujarati theatre]]\n[[Category:20th-century Indian dramatists and playwrights]]\n[[Category:20th-century Indian male actors]]\n[[Category:People from Mumbai]]\n[[Category:1934 births]]\n[[Category:1979 deaths]]\n", "name_user": "Imkruti", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Pravin_Joshi"}
{"title_page": "Darryl Duffy", "text_new": "{{EngvarB|date=July 2013}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2017}}\n{{Infobox football biography\n| name = Darryl Duffy\n| image = \n| caption = \n| fullname = Darryl Alexander Duffy<ref>{{Hugman|22898|accessdate=11 March 2017}}</ref>\n| birth_date = {{Birth date and age|1984|4|16|df=y}}\n| birth_place = [[Glasgow]], Scotland\n| height = \n| position = [[Striker (association football)|Striker]]\n| currentclub = [[Stirling Albion F.C.|Stirling Albion]]\n| clubnumber =\n| years1 = 2003\u20132004\n| clubs1 = [[Rangers F.C.|Rangers]]\n| caps1 = 1\n| goals1 = 0\n| years2 = 2004\n| clubs2 = \u2192 [[Brechin City F.C.|Brechin City]] (loan)\n| caps2 = 8\n| goals2 = 4\n| years3 = 2004\u20132006\n| clubs3 = [[Falkirk F.C.|Falkirk]]\n| caps3 = 57\n| goals3 = 27\n| years4 = 2006\u20132007\n| clubs4 = [[Hull City A.F.C.|Hull City]]\n| caps4 = 24\n| goals4 = 3\n| years5 = 2006\n| clubs5 = \u2192 [[Hartlepool United F.C.|Hartlepool United]] (loan)\n| caps5 = 10\n| goals5 = 5\n| years6 = 2007\n| clubs6 = \u2192 [[Swansea City A.F.C.|Swansea City]] (loan)\n| caps6 = 8\n| goals6 = 5\n| years7 = 2007\u20132008\n| clubs7 = [[Swansea City A.F.C.|Swansea City]]\n| caps7 = 20\n| goals7 = 1\n| years8 = 2008\u20132011\n| clubs8 = [[Bristol Rovers F.C.|Bristol Rovers]]\n| caps8 = 76\n| goals8 = 21\n| years9 = 2010\n| clubs9 = \u2192 [[Carlisle United F.C.|Carlisle United]] (loan)\n| caps9 = 8\n| goals9 = 1\n| years10 = 2010\u20132011\n| clubs10 = \u2192 [[Hibernian F.C.|Hibernian]] (loan)\n| caps10 = 7\n| goals10 = 0\n| years11 = 2011\u20132013\n| caps11 = 65\n| goals11 = 18\n| clubs11 = [[Cheltenham Town F.C.|Cheltenham Town]]\n| years12 = 2013\u20132016\n| caps12 = 49\n| goals12 = 32\n| clubs12 = [[Salgaocar F.C.|Salgaocar]]\n| years13 = 2015\n| caps13 = 4\n| goals13 = 0\n| clubs13 = \u2192 [[FC Goa|Goa]] (loan)\n| years14 = 2016\u20132017\n| caps14 = 17\n| goals14 = 11\n| clubs14 = [[Mohun Bagan A.C.|Mohun Bagan]]\n| years15 = 2017\u20132018\n| caps15 = 2\n| goals15 = 0\n| clubs15 = [[St Mirren F.C.|St Mirren]]\n| years16 = 2018\n| caps16 = 10\n| goals16 = 4\n| clubs16 = \u2192 [[Airdrieonians F.C.|Airdrieonians]] (loan)\n| years17 = 2018\u20132019\n| caps17 = 32\n| goals17 = 10\n| clubs17 = [[Airdrieonians F.C.|Airdrieonians]]\n| years18 = 2019\u2013\n| caps18 = 14\n| goals18 = 2\n| clubs18 = [[Stirling Albion F.C.|Stirling Albion]]\n| nationalyears1 = 2005\n| nationalteam1 = [[Scotland national under-21 football team|Scotland U21]]\n| nationalcaps1 = 8\n| nationalgoals1 = 4\n| nationalyears2 = 2005\u20132006\n| nationalteam2 = [[Scotland B national football team|Scotland B]]\n| nationalcaps2 = 2\n| nationalgoals2 = 0\n| club-update = 31 December 2019 (UTC)\n| ntupdate = \n}}\n\n'''Darryl Alexander Duffy''' (born 16 April 1984) is a Scottish [[Association football|footballer]] who plays as a [[Striker (association football)|striker]] for [[Stirling Albion F.C.|Stirling Albion]]. He began playing professionally in 2003 and has played for fifteen different teams across a number of countries. He played for [[Scotland national under-21 football team|Scotland U21s]] in 2005 and [[Scotland B national football team|Scotland B]] in 2005\u20132006.\n\n==Club career==\n\n===Scotland===\nBorn in [[Glasgow]], Duffy made his debut for [[Rangers F.C.|Rangers]] in a [[Scottish League Cup]] match against [[Forfar Athletic F.C.|Forfar]] on 28 October 2003,<ref name=\"Four\"/> coming on as an 84th-minute substitute for [[Maurice Ross]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Rangers 6\u20130 Forfar Athletic|url=http://www.rangers.co.uk/match/match-reports/2003-04/item/4207-rangers-6-0-forfar-athletic|publisher=Rangers|accessdate=5 August 2015|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150924111529/http://www.rangers.co.uk/match/match-reports/2003-04/item/4207-rangers-6-0-forfar-athletic|archivedate=24 September 2015|df=dmy-all}}</ref> Two months later, 19 year old Duffy would make his league debut, in a 2\u20131 win over [[Dundee United F.C.|Dundee]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Rangers 2\u20131 Dundee United|url=http://www.rangers.co.uk/match/match-reports/2003-04/item/4199-rangers-2-1-dundee-united|publisher=Rangers|accessdate=5 August 2015|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150924111526/http://www.rangers.co.uk/match/match-reports/2003-04/item/4199-rangers-2-1-dundee-united|archivedate=24 September 2015|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nAfter rejecting an offer from [[Queen of the South F.C.|Queen of the South]], Duffy signed for [[Falkirk F.C.|Falkirk]] the following June. The then Falkirk manager [[John Hughes (footballer, born 1964)|John Hughes]] said that some \"other clubs\" from Scotland as well as from abroad were also interested in his signature.<ref>{{cite web|title=Falkirk win Duffy chase|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/football/teams/f/falkirk/3841357.stm|publisher=BBC|accessdate=5 August 2015}}</ref> He scored on his debut in a [[Scottish League Challenge Cup]] against [[Ayr F.C.|Ayr]].<ref name=\"Falkirk put the wheels in motion\">{{cite web|title=Falkirk put the wheels in motion|url=http://www.scotsman.com/sport/football/latest/falkirk-put-the-wheels-in-motion-1-1396509|publisher=Scotsman|accessdate=5 August 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Bell's Cup first round|url=http://www.scotsman.com/sport/football/latest/bell-s-cup-first-round-1-1396343|publisher=Scotsman|accessdate=5 August 2015}}</ref> In the following month, he would start his scoring with a brace against [[Montrose F.C.|Montrose]], finding the net in the 15th and 31st minute of a 4\u20131 victory.<ref>{{cite web|title=Falkirk 4\u20131 Montrose|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/football/scot_div_1/3552892.stm|publisher=BBC|accessdate=5 August 2015}}</ref> This would mark a start of nine goals in seven matches, and come the end of the season, Duffy would score a total of 27 goals in 44 appearances.<ref name=\"Five\"/> His goal against [[St Johnstone F.C.|St Johnstone]] would help Falkirk move to third place in the league table<ref>{{cite web|title=Falkirk 3\u20130 St Johnstone|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/football/scot_div_1/4401801.stm|publisher=BBC|accessdate=5 August 2015}}</ref> and Falkirk would end the season as the champions of the [[Scottish First Division]], thus winning promotion to [[Scottish Premier League]].<ref>{{cite web|title=2004/05 Scottish Division One|url=http://www.soccerbase.com/tournaments/tournament.sd?tourn_id=894|publisher=Soccerbase|accessdate=5 August 2015}}</ref> He also went on to bag the Young Player of the Year award, along with the Young Player of August award.<ref>{{cite web|title=Bell''s Monthly Award Winners Season 2004/05|url=http://spfl.co.uk/news/article/the-annual-bell-s-awards-took-place/|publisher=Scottish Premier Football League|accessdate=5 August 2015}}</ref> At the start of the new season, he was linked with a move away from the club, even though manager Hughes was optimistic of keeping him. In an interview to the club's website, he said \"I've spoken to Darryl and he is fully committed to Falkirk FC.\"<ref>{{cite web|title=Falkirk out to keep hold of Duffy|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/football/teams/f/falkirk/4107166.stm|publisher=BBC|accessdate=5 August 2015}}</ref> Duffy's first goal in the Premier League would come against [[Livingston F.C.|Livingston]]. In the 2\u20130 victory, his 72nd minute shot would find the net, due to a deflection off [[Greg Strong]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Livingston 0\u20132 Falkirk|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/football/scot_prem/4748397.stm|publisher=BBC|accessdate=5 August 2015}}</ref> He would play a total of 16 matches, scoring nine goals in the top tier of the Scottish League until his transfer to [[Hull City A.F.C.|Hull City]].<ref>{{cite web|title=6 former young players of the month who 'vanished'|url=http://www.scotsman.com/sport/football/latest/6-former-young-players-of-the-month-who-vanished-1-3306809|publisher=Scotsman|accessdate=5 August 2015}}</ref>\n\n===England===\nDuffy joined [[Hull City A.F.C.|Hull City]] on 10 January 2006, penning a two and a half year contract. Falkirk chairman [[Campbell Christie]] expressed his disappointment about the transfer saying that Duffy wanted to \"develop\" his career in England.<ref name=\"Hull sign Falkirk striker Duffy\">{{cite news| title = Hull sign Falkirk striker Duffy| url = http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/teams/f/falkirk/4597086.stm| publisher = BBC Sport| date = 10 January 2006| accessdate = 25 February 2007}}</ref> Though ''[[British Broadcasting Company|BBC]]'' wrote that the transfer fee was \u00a3250,000, ''[[The Guardian]]'' said that he joined the club for an undisclosed fee.<ref>{{cite web|title=Original Comic Gems; and Stan 'n' Sobby|url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2006/jan/10/thefiver.sport|publisher=The Guardian|accessdate=5 August 2015}}</ref> However, with limited opportunities at Hull, particularly after the departure of manager [[Peter Taylor (footballer born 1953)|Peter Taylor]], he joined [[Hartlepool United F.C.|Hartlepool United]] on [[loan (football)|loan]] in November 2006, scoring 5 goals in 10 games for the then [[Football League Two|League Two]] side.\n\nAn even more productive loan spell followed in February 2007, when Duffy joined [[Football League One|League One]] side [[Swansea City A.F.C.|Swansea City]] on loan, scoring five goals in as many starts, as the Swans narrowly missed out on the playoffs. In July 2007 Duffy joined Swansea permanently, signing a three-year contract for an initial fee of \u00a3200,000.<ref>{{cite news| title = Swansea end Duffy transfer saga| url = http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/teams/s/swansea_city/6222952.stm| publisher = BBC Sport| date = 10 July 2007| accessdate = 10 July 2007}}</ref>\n\n[[Bristol Rovers F.C.|Bristol Rovers]] signed Duffy from Swansea on 3 July 2008 for a transfer fee in the region of \u00a3100,000.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/teams/b/bristol_rovers/7488124.stm |title=Duffy seals Bristol Rovers switch |date=3 August 2008 |work=BBC Sport |accessdate=3 August 2008}}</ref> Duffy scored twice in a 6\u20131 over [[Hereford United F.C.|Hereford United]] and in a 2\u20132 draw at [[Elland Road]] against [[Leeds United F.C.|Leeds United]]. At the end of the 2008\u201309 season, Duffy had scored 13 goals for Rovers. After this, however, Duffy's first team opportunities were restricted.<ref name = \"hibs loan\">{{cite news |url=http://www.heraldscotland.com/sport/spl/hibernian/darryl-duffy-hopes-he-can-rediscover-his-best-form-under-john-hughes-at-hibs-1.1051661 |last=Collin |first=Iain |title=Darryl Duffy hopes he can rediscover his best form under John Hughes at Hibs |work=[[The Herald (Glasgow)|The Herald]] |date=31 August 2010 |accessdate=31 August 2010}}</ref> He had a loan spell at [[Carlisle United]]<ref>{{cite news| title = Carlisle seal deals for Ben Marshall and Darryl Duffy | url = http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/teams/c/carlisle_united/8491423.stm| publisher = BBC Sport| date = 1 February 2010| accessdate = 5 October 2013}}</ref> where he scored once against [[MK Dons]].<ref>{{cite news| title = Carlisle 5 \u2013 0 MK Dons| url = http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/eng_div_2/8494112.stm| publisher = BBC Sport| date = 13 February 2010| accessdate = 5 October 2013}}</ref>\n\nOn 30 August 2010, Duffy signed a season-long loan deal with [[Scottish Premier League|SPL]] side [[Hibernian F.C.|Hibernian]] to team up with his former [[Falkirk F.C.|Falkirk]] manager [[John Hughes (footballer born 1964)|John Hughes]].<ref>{{cite news |url=http://sport.stv.tv/football/scottish-premier/hibernian/194718-hibs-sign-duffy-on-loan/ |title=Hibs sign Duffy on loan |publisher=[[STV (TV network)|STV]] |date=30 August 2010 |accessdate=30 August 2010}}</ref> Duffy was ostensibly signed by Hibs as a replacement for [[Anthony Stokes]],<ref name = \"hibs loan\"/> but suffered a foot injury soon after signing for the club.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.dailyrecord.co.uk/football/spl/2010/09/12/hibs-1-inverness-ct-1-86908-22555535/ |title=Hibs 1 Inverness CT 1 |last=Fairburn |first=Rob |work=[[Sunday Mail (Scotland)|Sunday Mail]] |date=12 September 2010 |accessdate=12 September 2010}}</ref> The injury meant that Duffy was unable to play for Hibs before Hughes left the club by mutual consent.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.dailyrecord.co.uk/football/spl/hibernian/2010/10/06/i-m-gutted-i-couldn-t-save-john-hughes-from-the-axe-admits-darryl-duffy-86908-22612547/ |last=Orr |first=Ian |work=[[Daily Record (Scotland)|Daily Record]] |date=7 October 2010 |accessdate=9 October 2010 |title=I'm gutted I couldn't save John Hughes from the axe, admits Darryl Duffy}}</ref> Duffy featured infrequently after he returned from injury and Hibs announced in April 2011 that he would return to Bristol after the loan deal was completed.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/13242007.stm|title=Hibernian to release 10 players|publisher=BBC |work=BBC Sport |date=29 April 2011|accessdate=29 April 2011}}</ref>\n\nDuffy was one of seventeen players released by Rovers in May 2011.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/13477210.stm |title=Midfielder Jeff Hughes heads Bristol Rovers exodus |publisher=BBC Sport|date=23 May 2011 |accessdate=23 May 2011}}</ref> [[Cheltenham Town F.C.|Cheltenham Town]] announced in July that they had agreed to sign Duffy.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/14232498.stm|title=Cheltenham Town set to sign striker Darryl Duffy|publisher=BBC Sport|date=21 July 2011 |accessdate=21 July 2011}}</ref> The striker hit his first goals for the club in a 3\u20132 win at [[Northampton Town F.C.|Northampton Town]]. He finished the 2011\u201312 season as top goalscorer with 15 goals.<ref name = \"india\"/> Cheltenham reached the League Two play-off final, but lost to [[Crewe Alexandra F.C.|Crewe]].<ref name = \"india\"/> Duffy then fell out of favour at Cheltenham, making just five starting appearances in the 2012\u201313 season.<ref name = \"india\"/> He was offered a new contract by Cheltenham in May 2013,<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/22575570 |title=Cheltenham Town: Marlon Pack among four offered new deals|work=BBC Sport |publisher=BBC |date=17 May 2013 |accessdate=4 October 2013}}</ref> but he decided to leave the club due to his frustration at not playing regularly.<ref name = \"india\"/>\n\n===India===\nAfter training with [[Kilmarnock F.C.|Kilmarnock]] during the 2013 close season, Duffy signed for Indian club [[Salgaocar F.C.|Salgaocar]].<ref name = \"india\">{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/24352543 |title=Darryl Duffy: From Football League to India's Premier League |work=BBC Sport |publisher=BBC |date=4 October 2013 |accessdate=4 October 2013 |first=Caroline |last=Chapman}}</ref> Duffy scored the winner on his debut for Salgaocar in their 1\u20130 win over [[Churchill Brothers S.C.|Churchill Brothers]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Churchill Brothers 0\u20131 Salgaocar|url=https://int.soccerway.com/matches/2013/09/21/india/i-league/churchill-brothers-sc/salgaocar-sports-club/1585275/|publisher=Soccerway|accessdate=18 October 2013}}</ref> Scottish striker scored 14 goals in 24 games for Salgaocar and won the Golden Boot in I-League along with [[Sunil Chhetri]].<ref name=THTProfessional>{{cite web|last=George|first=Joseph|title=Salgaocar's Darryl Duffy Raising The Bar Of Indian Football|url=http://www.thehardtackle.com/2013/salgaocars-darryl-duffy-raising-the-bar-of-indian-football/|work=The Hard Tackle|accessdate=4 November 2013}}</ref>\n\nOn 2 September 2015, he signed for [[Indian Super League]] franchise [[FC Goa]] on loan till the end of the season.<ref>{{cite web|title=ISL 2015: FC Goa sign Darryl Duffy, Luciano Sabrosa|url=http://www.ibnlive.com/news/sports/isl-2015-fc-goa-sign-darryl-duffy-luciano-sabrosa-1067715.html|publisher=IBN Live|accessdate=3 September 2015}}</ref> Duffy left Goa in October due to [[Bone fracture|hair line fracture]] on his shin bone.<ref name=\"Dudu to replace injured Duffy\">{{cite web|title=Dudu to replace injured Duffy|url=http://www.thehindu.com/sport/football/indian-super-league-2015-isl-2015-dudu-omagbemi-to-replace-injured-darryl-duffy-in-fc-goa/article7842012.ece|website=thehindu.com|publisher=The Hindu|accessdate=11 November 2015}}</ref>\n\nDuring the summer transfer window of 2016, Duffy signed for Mohun Bagan from Salgaocar fc. He played for Mohun Bagan in the [[Calcutta Football League]] where he scored 6 goals in 8 matches. Duffy scored a brace in [[I-League]] against [[Shillong Lajong F.C.|Shillong Lajong]] on 13 January 2017 and he was adjudged the man of the match.\n\n===Return to Scotland===\nDuffy signed a one-year deal with [[Scottish Championship]] club [[St Mirren F.C.|St Mirren]] on 10 August 2017.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.stmirren.com/news/club/all-news/1053-darryl-duffy-signs-for-st-mirren |title=Darryl Duffy signs for St Mirren |publisher=St Mirren FC |date=10 August 2017 |accessdate=10 August 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170810170639/https://www.stmirren.com/news/club/all-news/1053-darryl-duffy-signs-for-st-mirren |archive-date=10 August 2017 |url-status=dead }}</ref> After finding it difficult to break into the first team, Duffy was loaned out to [[Scottish League One]] club [[Airdrieonians F.C.|Airdrieonians]] on 10 January 2018, for the remainder of the season.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.airdriefc.com/darrylduffy-100118 |title=Darryl Duffy joins on loan |publisher=Airdrieonians FC |date=10 August 2017 |accessdate=10 August 2017}}</ref> Duffy was released by St Mirren at the end of the season,<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.stmirren.com/news/club/all-news/1849-players-depart-club |title=Players Depart Club |work= |publisher=St Mirren FC |date=30 April 2018 |accessdate=30 April 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180430181942/https://www.stmirren.com/news/club/all-news/1849-players-depart-club |archive-date=30 April 2018 |url-status=dead }}</ref> and subsequently returned to Airdrieonians on a permanent deal in May 2018.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.airdriefc.com/darrylduffy-210518 |title=Darryl Duffy makes Excelsior return |publisher=Airdrieonians FC |date=21 May 2018 |accessdate=21 May 2018}}</ref> \n\n==International career==\nDuffy was selected for [[Scotland B national football team|Scotland B]] against Poland and [[Turkey B national football team|Turkey]] during the 2005 Future Cup.<ref>[http://www.scottishfa.co.uk/scottish_football.cfm?curpageid=482 FUTURE CUP 2005] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080701214004/http://www.scottishfa.co.uk/scottish_football.cfm?curpageid=482 |date=1 July 2008 }}, [[Scottish Football Association]].</ref>\n\n==Career statistics==\n{{updated|26 November 2017}}<ref>{{cite web|title=Darryl Duffy career statistics|url=https://int.soccerway.com/players/darryl-duffy/50852/|publisher=Soccerway|accessdate=23 October 2013}}</ref>\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align: center;\"\n|-\n!rowspan=\"2\"|Club\n!rowspan=\"2\"|Season\n!colspan=\"3\"|League\n!colspan=\"2\"|Cup<ref>Includes [[Scottish League Cup]], [[Scottish Challenge Cup]], [[FA Cup]], [[English League Cup]], [[English Football League Trophy]] and [[Federation Cup (India)|Federation Cup]]</ref>\n!colspan=\"2\"|Continental<ref>Includes [[UEFA Champions League]]</ref>\n!colspan=\"2\"|Total\n|-\n!Division!!Apps!!Goals!!Apps!!Goals!!Apps!!Goals!!Apps!!Goals\n|-\n|[[Rangers F.C.|Rangers]]\n|[[2003\u201304 Scottish Premier League|2003\u201304]]<ref name=\"Four\">{{Soccerbase season|36689|2003|accessdate=23 October 2013}}</ref>\n|[[Scottish Premier League]]\n|1||0||1||0||1||0||3||0\n|-\n|rowspan=\"3\"|[[Falkirk F.C.|Falkirk]]\n|[[2004\u201305 Scottish First Division|2004\u201305]]<ref name=\"Five\">{{Soccerbase season|36689|2004|accessdate=23 O